WEBVTT

00:09.051 --> 00:12.054
<i>[rocking chair creaking]</i>

00:16.058 --> 00:19.061
<i>[eerie music]</i>

00:19.061 --> 00:22.940
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:22.940 --> 00:25.317
<i>MARY: We all die.</i>

00:25.317 --> 00:28.528
<i>But sometimes the tales</i>
<i>of our passing are so shocking</i>

00:28.528 --> 00:30.322
<i>that they must be</i>
<i>forever carved</i>

00:30.322 --> 00:34.076
<i>into our collective memory.</i>

00:34.076 --> 00:36.662
<i>There is a place where</i>
<i>these horrors are transcribed</i>

00:36.662 --> 00:39.331
<i>by the dead.</i>

00:39.331 --> 00:41.750
<i>And they want</i>
<i>their stories told.</i>

00:41.750 --> 00:44.920
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:44.920 --> 00:47.923
<i>[music builds]</i>

00:47.923 --> 00:54.930
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:13.073 --> 01:14.992
[door creaks]

01:17.995 --> 01:19.413
[books crash]

01:24.501 --> 01:26.378
[distant clanging]

01:26.378 --> 01:29.381
<i>[ominous music]</i>

01:29.381 --> 01:36.388
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:50.110 --> 01:51.945
[distant clanging]

01:51.945 --> 01:55.240
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:55.240 --> 01:56.825
<i>[ominous beat]</i>

01:56.825 --> 01:59.202
[door creaks]

01:59.202 --> 02:03.206
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:03.206 --> 02:06.168
<i>[dramatic musical sting]</i>

02:06.168 --> 02:13.175
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:16.970 --> 02:19.973
‐ [grunting]

02:19.973 --> 02:23.352
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:23.352 --> 02:27.189
[moans]

02:27.189 --> 02:29.650
Bennett, look, I‐I told you,
I can pay!

02:29.650 --> 02:31.068
I just need time.

02:31.068 --> 02:32.444
‐ Time ran out.

02:32.444 --> 02:33.862
They want blood now.

02:33.862 --> 02:35.656
‐ I have something.

02:35.656 --> 02:37.324
Something very valuable.

02:37.324 --> 02:38.450
It's a book.

02:38.450 --> 02:40.869
It's a rare book
worth millions.

02:40.869 --> 02:42.037
‐ Go on.

02:42.037 --> 02:43.538
BOOKMAN: I can tell you
where to find it.

02:43.538 --> 02:46.541
<i>[Marilyn Manson's "Deep Six"]</i>

02:46.541 --> 02:50.003
<i>[dark rock music]</i>

02:50.003 --> 02:51.421
<i>MANSON:</i>
<i>♪ Yeah ♪</i>

02:51.421 --> 02:54.091
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:55.092 --> 02:56.593
‐ Thanks.

02:56.593 --> 02:59.721
<i>[ominous music]</i>

02:59.721 --> 03:06.728
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:12.609 --> 03:14.695
MANSON:
♪ Deep six, six, six ♪

03:14.695 --> 03:18.115
♪ Six, six feet deep ♪

03:18.115 --> 03:19.825
[tires squeal, engine revving]

03:19.825 --> 03:21.827
♪ Deep six, six, six ♪

03:21.827 --> 03:24.871
♪ Six, six feet deep ♪

03:24.871 --> 03:26.164
♪ ♪

03:26.164 --> 03:28.917
‐ He tried
to buy himself loose.

03:28.917 --> 03:30.043
Gave me a tip on something

03:30.043 --> 03:31.962
that could be our shot
at cashing out.

03:31.962 --> 03:33.422
‐ Oh, yeah?

03:33.422 --> 03:35.715
‐ A book.

03:35.715 --> 03:37.634
One of a kind, apparently.

03:37.634 --> 03:40.429
‐ Where?

03:40.429 --> 03:42.222
‐ Ravenmoor.

03:42.222 --> 03:44.474
‐ You do know that place is
royally fucked up, right?

03:44.474 --> 03:45.600
Something happened there.

03:45.600 --> 03:47.978
They say it's like
fucking Chernobyl.

03:47.978 --> 03:49.229
‐ Urban decay.

03:49.229 --> 03:50.814
That's what happened.
[phone beeps]

03:50.814 --> 03:55.318
<i>GPS: Begin route to Ravenmoor,</i>
<i>47 Tollington Place.</i>

03:55.318 --> 03:56.778
‐ You want to run
with the fucking rats

03:56.778 --> 03:58.488
the rest of your life?

03:58.488 --> 04:00.657
‐ What's this book called?

04:00.657 --> 04:02.784
<i>‐ The Book of Blood.</i>

04:02.784 --> 04:05.787
<i>[tense music]</i>

04:05.787 --> 04:12.752
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:16.214 --> 04:19.217
<i>[eerie music]</i>

04:19.217 --> 04:26.224
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:48.371 --> 04:51.374
<i>[ominous music]</i>

04:51.374 --> 04:58.340
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:12.145 --> 05:14.272
NICOLE:
That's why I bought this place.

05:14.272 --> 05:15.315
The view.

05:15.315 --> 05:16.900
It's so beautiful.

05:16.900 --> 05:18.902
‐ So desolate.

05:22.197 --> 05:25.700
‐ It's like we're looking
at two different places.

05:25.700 --> 05:27.536
‐ Ten minutes
in that hellish water,

05:27.536 --> 05:30.163
and you'd freeze to death.

05:30.163 --> 05:32.249
‐ Why do you do that,

05:32.249 --> 05:36.294
and why can't you just
enjoy anything?

05:36.294 --> 05:38.505
What happened at school is
on him,

05:38.505 --> 05:40.298
not on you.

05:40.298 --> 05:42.050
‐ You don't know what happened.

05:42.050 --> 05:43.552
‐ Tell me.

05:43.552 --> 05:45.345
Tell someone.

05:45.345 --> 05:47.013
I mean, how do you expect us
to help you

05:47.013 --> 05:49.015
if you're not willing to talk
about it?

05:52.644 --> 05:55.355
Maybe Dr. Lerner needs to tweak
your meds.

05:57.732 --> 05:59.401
‐ I stopped taking them.

05:59.401 --> 06:01.319
NICOLE: What?

06:01.319 --> 06:03.989
‐ Yeah, I stopped taking
the meds, like, a week ago.

06:03.989 --> 06:06.575
‐ You can't just stop
your meds, Jenna.

06:06.575 --> 06:08.743
The doctor was very clear
about that.

06:08.743 --> 06:11.580
‐ They weren't helping.

06:11.580 --> 06:14.749
They just made me feel tired
and numb all the time.

06:14.749 --> 06:18.461
‐ Tired and numb is better
than having a broken brain.

06:18.461 --> 06:20.589
‐ Yeah, well,

06:20.589 --> 06:22.716
you're not the one
who has to take them.

06:26.261 --> 06:29.848
NICOLE: Dinner's ready,
if you're interested.

06:32.809 --> 06:34.644
DAN:
Hello, Princess.

06:34.644 --> 06:38.064
JENNA: Women prefer
to be called queens now, Dan.

06:38.064 --> 06:40.191
Show a little respect.

06:40.191 --> 06:41.776
‐ For what?

06:41.776 --> 06:45.322
When I was your age, I wouldn't
be caught dead living at home.

06:45.322 --> 06:47.073
JENNA:
What does that even mean?

06:47.073 --> 06:49.868
‐ What?
‐ "Caught dead."

06:49.868 --> 06:52.162
‐ You know,
that's your problem, Jen.

06:52.162 --> 06:53.997
You're so lost in the trees

06:53.997 --> 06:55.498
that you can't even see
the leaves.

06:55.498 --> 06:57.042
DAN: The forest.

06:57.042 --> 06:58.918
I think that's what you can't
see for the trees.

06:58.918 --> 07:00.629
[laughs]

07:04.215 --> 07:07.218
[chewing]

07:12.223 --> 07:15.226
[loud chewing]

07:15.226 --> 07:16.936
[slurping]

07:16.936 --> 07:19.272
[swallows]

07:19.272 --> 07:22.275
[chewing crescendos]

07:22.275 --> 07:24.611
[chair scrapes]

07:24.611 --> 07:27.155
‐ Oh, here we go‐‐
Jenna off her meds.

07:27.155 --> 07:29.240
You want me to dissolve
the food in my mouth?

07:29.240 --> 07:31.826
I mean, how can I eat
without chewing, Jenna?

07:31.826 --> 07:33.161
You're getting back
on those meds,

07:33.161 --> 07:37.123
because I am not going down
that road again.

07:37.123 --> 07:40.835
[waves crashing]

07:42.295 --> 07:46.216
Three different shrinks
since she was 10 years old.

07:46.216 --> 07:49.052
Tutoring and private coaches
to get her into college,

07:49.052 --> 07:51.221
and then she flushes it
down the shithole.

07:51.221 --> 07:53.473
‐ You said yourself
she was a victim, too,

07:53.473 --> 07:55.016
so don't blame the victim.

07:55.016 --> 07:56.893
NICOLE: I don't want to blame
the victim.

07:56.893 --> 07:58.436
I want to bill the victim.

07:58.436 --> 08:00.188
I'm sending her back
to the farm.

08:00.188 --> 08:02.399
And you know what?
If she fucks it up, I am done.

08:02.399 --> 08:04.943
They're coming
to get her tomorrow.

08:04.943 --> 08:07.946
<i>[ominous music]</i>

08:07.946 --> 08:14.911
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:14.911 --> 08:17.914
[waves crashing]

08:20.208 --> 08:22.127
[laughter]

08:22.127 --> 08:24.379
Get over here.

08:24.379 --> 08:26.131
Oh, my‐‐
[laughs]

08:26.131 --> 08:28.049
[laughter]

08:28.049 --> 08:30.093
[laughter cuts off]

09:01.750 --> 09:08.715
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:28.860 --> 09:30.737
[door creaks]

09:30.737 --> 09:33.156
[both grunt]

09:33.156 --> 09:40.163
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:06.147 --> 10:07.232
‐ Excuse me.

10:07.232 --> 10:08.942
Has the bus for Los Angeles
left yet?

10:08.942 --> 10:10.235
ATTENDANT:
Leaves in five minutes.

10:10.235 --> 10:12.320
‐ Great.
I need to get a ticket.

10:12.320 --> 10:13.446
Please.

10:30.046 --> 10:36.886
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:36.886 --> 10:39.514
[mop squishes]

10:39.514 --> 10:41.516
<i>ANNOUNCER: Last call.</i>
<i>Now boarding.</i>

10:41.516 --> 10:44.519
<i>[indistinct announcement]</i>

10:44.519 --> 10:51.568
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:58.491 --> 11:02.579
[crunching and chewing]

11:02.579 --> 11:06.541
[people coughing]

11:06.541 --> 11:09.294
[loud chewing]

11:15.800 --> 11:19.262
[loud crunching and chewing]

11:19.262 --> 11:22.432
[chewing crescendos]

11:22.432 --> 11:25.185
[chewing cuts off]

11:25.185 --> 11:28.062
‐ [sighs]

11:28.062 --> 11:29.314
[muffled]
Okay.

11:29.314 --> 11:33.526
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:33.526 --> 11:37.071
[mysterious beating]

11:37.071 --> 11:43.453
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:43.453 --> 11:46.456
<i>[music building]</i>

11:46.456 --> 11:53.421
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:16.277 --> 12:18.905
[mysterious beating]

12:25.078 --> 12:32.043
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:01.239 --> 13:02.615
[horn blares]

13:02.615 --> 13:04.242
[tires squeal]

13:07.704 --> 13:11.332
<i>[tense music]</i>

13:11.332 --> 13:13.584
[door squeaks]

13:13.584 --> 13:20.591
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:27.473 --> 13:30.018
[indistinct chatter]

13:44.323 --> 13:46.325
<i>ELLIE: Very pleased</i>
<i>to meet you, Jenna.</i>

13:46.325 --> 13:48.286
Now, you just rest here
a moment

13:48.286 --> 13:50.913
while we go
get your room ready.

13:50.913 --> 13:52.540
Okay?

13:52.540 --> 13:55.752
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:59.797 --> 14:01.799
‐ [shivers]

14:07.305 --> 14:09.640
‐ I knew it.

14:09.640 --> 14:11.934
‐ What?
‐ I just saw you in the web...

14:11.934 --> 14:14.062
at Spider's Web Café.

14:14.062 --> 14:15.229
‐ Oh.

14:15.229 --> 14:16.731
‐ It's, um...
God, what's the word?

14:16.731 --> 14:19.108
Like a‐‐like a coincidence

14:19.108 --> 14:21.569
but more cosmic or something?

14:21.569 --> 14:22.695
‐ Synchronicity?

14:22.695 --> 14:23.946
‐ Right, synchronicity.
That's it.

14:23.946 --> 14:26.032
Like a...

14:26.032 --> 14:29.285
a meaningful coincidence.

14:29.285 --> 14:31.621
‐ Your folks seem so nice.

14:31.621 --> 14:33.706
‐ No,
they're a total nightmare.

14:33.706 --> 14:36.292
Fortunately, they're back home
in Sydney.

14:36.292 --> 14:39.212
‐ Oh.
So you're not family?

14:39.212 --> 14:42.757
‐ We like to think everyone
who stays here is family.

14:42.757 --> 14:44.425
‐ It's destiny.

14:44.425 --> 14:47.261
‐ Or synchronicity.

14:47.261 --> 14:48.513
‐ Hmm.

14:53.768 --> 14:55.937
[exhales deeply]

15:02.985 --> 15:04.987
[sighs]

15:12.495 --> 15:15.498
[light tapping]

15:21.295 --> 15:22.755
[wood creaks]

15:35.017 --> 15:36.769
[sighs]

15:47.613 --> 15:50.616
[faint scratching]

16:01.961 --> 16:04.964
[scratching]

16:08.593 --> 16:11.596
[loud scratching]

16:11.596 --> 16:13.222
[gasps]

16:13.222 --> 16:14.348
BOTH:
Oh!

16:14.348 --> 16:15.683
‐ Oh.
‐ Oh, I'm so sorry, dear.

16:15.683 --> 16:17.810
‐ That's okay.
‐ I didn't mean to startle you.

16:17.810 --> 16:19.437
Are you all right, dear?

16:19.437 --> 16:21.022
JENNA: Yeah.

16:21.022 --> 16:24.692
Yeah.
I just think I'm really tired.

16:24.692 --> 16:26.569
‐ I saw you must love music,

16:26.569 --> 16:28.779
so I put a radio
right by your bed.

16:28.779 --> 16:31.407
‐ I don't really like music.

16:31.407 --> 16:34.243
These are just so that
I don't...

16:34.243 --> 16:35.995
hear anything.

16:35.995 --> 16:37.538
‐ Oh, I understand.

16:37.538 --> 16:39.665
You're sensitive.

16:39.665 --> 16:41.834
Of course.
You're an artist.

16:41.834 --> 16:44.295
‐ No, these are just, uh...

16:44.295 --> 16:46.130
drawings.

16:48.299 --> 16:51.928
‐ In a strange town,
in a stranger's home,

16:51.928 --> 16:55.056
after a long night journey...

16:55.056 --> 16:57.099
For moments like these,

16:57.099 --> 17:00.478
the good Lord gave us tea
and cake.

17:00.478 --> 17:02.146
Come.

17:07.902 --> 17:09.862
JENNA: I wasn't planning
on stopping.

17:09.862 --> 17:11.572
I was, um‐‐

17:11.572 --> 17:14.575
I‐I was headed to LA,
and I just...

17:14.575 --> 17:17.119
couldn't stand the thought
of, uh, being nauseous

17:17.119 --> 17:19.497
for a day and a half on a bus.

17:19.497 --> 17:22.833
‐ I'm sure
you weren't nauseous, dear.

17:22.833 --> 17:25.086
‐ Oh, but I was.

17:25.086 --> 17:27.463
‐ Nauseous means you make
other people sick.

17:27.463 --> 17:30.508
Nauseated is what you were.

17:30.508 --> 17:33.511
‐ Ellie is very particular
about words,

17:33.511 --> 17:35.513
especially medical words.

17:35.513 --> 17:38.182
See, Ellie was
a registered nurse‐‐

17:38.182 --> 17:40.518
you know, someone that does
what a doctor does

17:40.518 --> 17:42.603
for a dime, not a dollar.

17:42.603 --> 17:44.730
‐ Now, Sam Austin,
that is not true.

17:44.730 --> 17:47.066
Doctors and nurses
are completely different.

17:47.066 --> 17:48.818
Doctors treat illnesses.

17:48.818 --> 17:51.696
Nurses treat people.

17:51.696 --> 17:53.823
‐ As for me, I don't know
what to do with my hands

17:53.823 --> 17:55.825
if I'm not building.

17:55.825 --> 17:59.954
I did the chairs
and this table.

17:59.954 --> 18:02.790
Just did the cabinets.

18:02.790 --> 18:06.377
Carved my own wooden leg.

18:06.377 --> 18:07.420
No, kidding.

18:07.420 --> 18:10.006
[both laugh]

18:10.006 --> 18:11.507
Can you imagine?

18:11.507 --> 18:14.385
[scratching]
‐ So did you build this house?

18:14.385 --> 18:16.554
SAM: We just added
here and there.

18:16.554 --> 18:18.639
ELLIE:
Oh, he's such a modest mouse.

18:18.639 --> 18:20.891
He doubled the size
of this place.

18:20.891 --> 18:22.351
[scratching continues]

18:22.351 --> 18:23.728
SAM: When you start
fixing things,

18:23.728 --> 18:24.729
you know how it is.

18:24.729 --> 18:26.606
There's always something else.

18:26.606 --> 18:29.025
‐ Oh, no, don't.

18:31.402 --> 18:33.446
‐ Yeah, a little bit
of a roach problem.

18:33.446 --> 18:35.281
Don't worry about it.

18:35.281 --> 18:39.201
I say we should just gas 'em,
but Ellie won't hear of that.

18:39.201 --> 18:42.955
‐ It's so much easier
to take life than to make life.

18:42.955 --> 18:45.082
[clock chimes and cuckoos]

18:45.082 --> 18:48.127
‐ And on that
cheery little note,

18:48.127 --> 18:50.504
this old man's going to bed.

18:50.504 --> 18:52.173
Good night, all.

18:55.134 --> 18:56.469
‐ What's in LA?

18:56.469 --> 18:58.512
‐ Oh.

18:58.512 --> 19:03.142
Tell you the truth,
I'm not sure where I'm going.

19:03.142 --> 19:04.810
‐ Maybe the only way to know
where you're headed

19:04.810 --> 19:07.355
is to keep going
till you find it.

19:07.355 --> 19:09.690
‐ Maybe.

19:09.690 --> 19:11.901
GAVIN: I'm just taking
some time to look around.

19:11.901 --> 19:15.529
How about you?

19:15.529 --> 19:18.741
You know what? Sorry.
That's none of my business.

19:21.035 --> 19:24.288
‐ I had a bad experience...

19:24.288 --> 19:27.041
at school with a guy.

19:27.041 --> 19:28.084
‐ Bad breakup?

19:28.084 --> 19:30.836
‐ More like a breakdown.

19:30.836 --> 19:33.547
Life sucks.

19:33.547 --> 19:35.049
‐ Yeah.

19:35.049 --> 19:37.385
Like my dad says,
we ain't born laughin'.

19:37.385 --> 19:38.886
‐ Hmm.

19:38.886 --> 19:40.846
Sounds like a smart man.

19:40.846 --> 19:43.391
GAVIN: You know his one
big piece of life advice‐‐

19:43.391 --> 19:46.602
in this world,
you're either the anvil

19:46.602 --> 19:48.813
or the hammer.

19:48.813 --> 19:50.690
Which do you want to be?

19:50.690 --> 19:53.275
‐ I'd rather be the ant.

19:53.275 --> 19:54.902
‐ What ant?

19:54.902 --> 19:57.196
‐ The ant crawling
across the anvil

19:57.196 --> 20:00.825
when the hammer comes down.

20:00.825 --> 20:03.327
Then at least
it's over quickly.

20:03.327 --> 20:06.288
‐ [chuckles]

20:06.288 --> 20:09.458
[slurps]

20:09.458 --> 20:11.127
Oh, um...

20:11.127 --> 20:12.545
uh, sorry?

20:12.545 --> 20:16.507
‐ I just have a thing
with mouth noises.

20:16.507 --> 20:18.008
Any noises, really.

20:18.008 --> 20:20.094
Sometimes I think
I'd just be happier deaf.

20:20.094 --> 20:21.512
‐ Oh, don't say that.

20:21.512 --> 20:23.681
JENNA: No, no, no.
It's a‐‐it's a thing.

20:23.681 --> 20:25.349
My doctor says
it's neurological.

20:25.349 --> 20:29.311
It's called misophonia‐‐
literally the hatred of sound.

20:29.311 --> 20:32.106
‐ Wow.
That must suck.

20:32.106 --> 20:33.274
‐ Would've probably been better

20:33.274 --> 20:35.151
if I'd just crawled
back into the womb

20:35.151 --> 20:36.861
and stayed there.

20:36.861 --> 20:39.488
‐ You're weird.

20:39.488 --> 20:41.157
I like weird.

20:52.042 --> 20:56.088
Hey, so I'm getting up early
to tour the college.

20:56.088 --> 20:57.506
You gonna be here tomorrow?

20:57.506 --> 21:00.468
‐ Not sure.

21:00.468 --> 21:02.136
I guess.

21:02.136 --> 21:06.682
‐ Well, uh, maybe
we could meet up for coffee.

21:06.682 --> 21:08.184
‐ Mm.

21:08.184 --> 21:10.227
Text me?

21:13.272 --> 21:15.274
[phones chime and buzz]

21:22.573 --> 21:25.451
[door creaks]

21:25.451 --> 21:28.579
[door closes, lock clicks]

21:28.579 --> 21:31.540
[insects chirping]

21:45.346 --> 21:47.765
[tapping]

21:47.765 --> 21:50.309
[scratching]

21:54.605 --> 21:56.649
[scratching cuts off]

21:56.649 --> 21:59.652
<i>[ominous music]</i>

21:59.652 --> 22:03.489
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:03.489 --> 22:06.659
[waves crashing]

22:06.659 --> 22:13.666
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:19.713 --> 22:21.632
<i>NICOLE:</i>
<i>She's fucking hopeless.</i>

22:21.632 --> 22:22.758
<i>I want her out.</i>

22:22.758 --> 22:29.139
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:29.139 --> 22:31.141
<i>[dramatic sting]</i>

22:31.141 --> 22:35.646
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:35.646 --> 22:38.691
[loud banging]

22:38.691 --> 22:43.779
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:43.779 --> 22:46.824
[loud thumping]

22:48.450 --> 22:51.453
<i>[eerie music]</i>

22:51.453 --> 22:58.419
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:59.545 --> 23:02.548
<i>[dramatic sting]</i>

23:02.548 --> 23:07.177
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:07.177 --> 23:11.015
[door creaks]

23:11.015 --> 23:18.063
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:33.621 --> 23:36.498
‐ [gasps]

23:36.498 --> 23:38.125
[knocking]

23:38.125 --> 23:45.090
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:55.100 --> 23:57.061
<i>[distorted, indistinct voice]</i>

23:57.061 --> 23:59.647
‐ Maybe Dr. Lerner needs
to tweak your meds.

23:59.647 --> 24:01.482
[voice echoes]

24:01.482 --> 24:08.447
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:20.501 --> 24:23.504
<i>[music building]</i>

24:23.504 --> 24:26.799
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:26.799 --> 24:28.425
[gurgling]

24:28.425 --> 24:29.426
‐ [retches]

24:29.426 --> 24:34.974
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:37.476 --> 24:40.479
[birds singing]

24:42.898 --> 24:46.402
[crows cawing]

24:51.115 --> 24:54.118
[hammer pounding]

24:58.622 --> 25:01.208
Morning.

25:01.208 --> 25:04.837
[cawing continues]

25:04.837 --> 25:08.632
‐ I do envy them.

25:08.632 --> 25:12.302
‐ Birds don't fly for pleasure.

25:12.302 --> 25:16.140
Flying is just an endless,
desperate search for food.

25:18.100 --> 25:20.019
‐ Well, it still looks fun.

25:30.696 --> 25:33.699
[silverware clattering,
indistinct chatter]

25:37.995 --> 25:40.372
[cup rattles]

25:40.372 --> 25:42.499
[mugs thump and clatter]

25:42.499 --> 25:44.376
[cups scrape]

25:44.376 --> 25:47.671
[loud chewing]

25:47.671 --> 25:50.215
[slurping]

25:52.176 --> 25:53.552
[sound cuts off]

25:53.552 --> 25:56.388
<i>[dark ambient music]</i>

25:56.388 --> 26:03.395
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:07.691 --> 26:10.611
‐ [sighs]

26:14.073 --> 26:15.783
[buzzes]

26:17.951 --> 26:20.954
[buzzing]

26:23.165 --> 26:24.374
[thumps]

26:26.627 --> 26:29.630
[chatter and clinking]

26:31.882 --> 26:33.008
SERVER: Can I help you?
‐ Hi.

26:33.008 --> 26:36.136
Can I get a, uh, large coffee
to go?

26:36.136 --> 26:37.763
Decaf.

26:45.145 --> 26:47.314
[sighs]

26:50.317 --> 26:53.320
<i>[ominous music]</i>

26:53.320 --> 26:59.660
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:59.660 --> 27:03.038
<i>[music building]</i>

27:03.038 --> 27:04.414
‐ Large decaf?
‐ [gasps]

27:04.414 --> 27:06.583
Oh.
Uh, no.

27:06.583 --> 27:08.460
I'm‐‐

27:08.460 --> 27:09.878
SERVER: Are you okay?

27:09.878 --> 27:13.465
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

27:13.465 --> 27:15.092
You can't go in there.

27:15.092 --> 27:22.099
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:40.284 --> 27:42.160
‐ Oh, my dear.

27:42.160 --> 27:45.038
What's wrong?
‐ Oh. Oh, I was just‐‐

27:45.038 --> 27:46.498
I was‐‐I was
supposed to meet Gavin,

27:46.498 --> 27:47.916
and then he didn't
show up and‐‐

27:47.916 --> 27:49.877
[breathing heavily]

27:49.877 --> 27:51.169
I don't know.
I don't know.

27:51.169 --> 27:54.965
Sometimes I see things
when I'm anxious, and...

27:54.965 --> 27:57.259
I just‐‐I‐‐

27:57.259 --> 27:59.887
‐ Poor bird.

27:59.887 --> 28:01.638
I'm working
in the garden today.

28:01.638 --> 28:03.765
Would you like to come see?

28:03.765 --> 28:06.059
There's nothing like
the quiet company of plants

28:06.059 --> 28:07.769
to calm a soul down.

28:07.769 --> 28:09.396
Hmm?

28:09.396 --> 28:12.441
<i>[serene music]</i>

28:12.441 --> 28:16.862
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:16.862 --> 28:18.155
Angelica‐‐

28:18.155 --> 28:20.115
excellent
for building strength.

28:20.115 --> 28:21.950
JENNA: Mm.

28:21.950 --> 28:23.785
‐ Oh, and here's basil.

28:23.785 --> 28:27.414
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:27.414 --> 28:30.167
Mmm.

28:30.167 --> 28:33.086
Bay leaf, coltsfoot,
devilwood...

28:33.086 --> 28:35.255
JENNA: Mm.
Devilwood sounds dangerous.

28:35.255 --> 28:36.798
‐ Oh, no, dear.

28:36.798 --> 28:38.842
Though if I put too much
in Sam's tea,

28:38.842 --> 28:41.386
he does get a bit persistent.

28:41.386 --> 28:44.473
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:44.473 --> 28:46.516
‐ What's that one?

28:46.516 --> 28:49.436
‐ Feverfew.

28:49.436 --> 28:52.105
As the name suggests,
better for a fever

28:52.105 --> 28:54.524
than anything you can buy
in the drugstore.

28:56.860 --> 28:58.695
First rule of gardening‐‐

28:58.695 --> 29:01.406
intruders must be weeded out.

29:01.406 --> 29:05.160
I hate to do it.
Weeds are plants, too.

29:05.160 --> 29:07.329
Got to protect the garden.

29:07.329 --> 29:11.208
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:11.208 --> 29:15.253
Sometimes
I can't help thinking...

29:15.253 --> 29:18.173
it'd be much nicer
to be a plant.

29:18.173 --> 29:21.093
Human life is so cruel...

29:21.093 --> 29:23.053
especially for mothers.

29:23.053 --> 29:26.640
Everything you birth
is taken away from you.

29:26.640 --> 29:29.142
Not here in my garden.

29:29.142 --> 29:33.313
Here, things stay
to grow where they're planted.

29:33.313 --> 29:36.274
‐ Do you have children?

29:36.274 --> 29:37.943
‐ Two.
JENNA: Mm.

29:37.943 --> 29:42.280
‐ My daughter Shiloh
and her twin brother Sam.

29:42.280 --> 29:45.325
Baby Sam...

29:45.325 --> 29:47.744
passed away
when they were newborns.

29:47.744 --> 29:49.705
‐ I'm so sorry.

29:49.705 --> 29:51.790
ELLIE: Thank you.

29:51.790 --> 29:54.251
And thank the good Lord
for Shiloh

29:54.251 --> 29:58.130
and my two beautiful grandkids.

29:58.130 --> 30:00.382
We're a tight‐knit family,

30:00.382 --> 30:02.592
and I intend to keep it
that way.

30:02.592 --> 30:06.179
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:06.179 --> 30:08.056
Honey?

30:08.056 --> 30:09.808
What's wrong?

30:09.808 --> 30:12.144
Trust Ellie.
Let it out.

30:12.144 --> 30:15.605
There's more room out here
than in there.

30:15.605 --> 30:18.608
<i>[tense music]</i>

30:18.608 --> 30:21.903
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:21.903 --> 30:24.906
‐ Something bad happened...

30:24.906 --> 30:28.160
at college.

30:28.160 --> 30:32.664
It just proved to me
what I always knew...

30:32.664 --> 30:35.751
what you just said...

30:35.751 --> 30:39.004
the world is
an ugly, cruel place.

30:39.004 --> 30:40.505
‐ Oh, my dear.

30:40.505 --> 30:43.300
It is. It is.

30:43.300 --> 30:45.427
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:45.427 --> 30:47.179
‐ And after what happened

30:47.179 --> 30:50.307
at school...

30:50.307 --> 30:53.643
I just didn't feel like myself.

30:53.643 --> 30:57.564
I felt like everyone
was staring at me.

30:57.564 --> 31:00.108
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:00.108 --> 31:01.610
I guess I got super paranoid

31:01.610 --> 31:04.529
because my mother sent me
to the farm.

31:04.529 --> 31:06.448
ELLIE:
The farm?

31:06.448 --> 31:08.658
‐ That's just
what they called it.

31:08.658 --> 31:11.953
The only vegetables they grew
there were the patients.

31:14.206 --> 31:16.917
And then after I left,

31:16.917 --> 31:19.294
it just got worse.

31:19.294 --> 31:22.589
ELLIE:
What did you do?

31:22.589 --> 31:26.051
‐ I stopped taking
my medication.

31:26.051 --> 31:29.721
ELLIE:
How did that feel?

31:29.721 --> 31:31.264
‐ Good.

31:31.264 --> 31:34.518
Really good...

31:34.518 --> 31:37.354
at first.

31:37.354 --> 31:39.773
And then, I don't know,
I just couldn't‐‐

31:39.773 --> 31:42.109
I couldn't stay there,
so‐‐so I ran,

31:42.109 --> 31:45.362
and then...

31:45.362 --> 31:46.404
ELLIE: What?

31:46.404 --> 31:48.740
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:48.740 --> 31:51.827
‐ No, it's‐‐it's stupid.

31:51.827 --> 31:55.664
‐ Stop judging your feelings
and just feel them.

31:55.664 --> 31:58.083
Now, what did you feel?

31:58.083 --> 32:00.836
‐ Followed.

32:00.836 --> 32:04.548
I felt like I was being
followed by someone,

32:04.548 --> 32:06.967
someone I'm pretty sure
doesn't even exist.

32:06.967 --> 32:09.261
‐ Who could it be?
JENNA: I don't know.

32:09.261 --> 32:12.472
I think I just made
a terrible mistake.

32:12.472 --> 32:14.933
Maybe I should be
in the hospital.

32:14.933 --> 32:17.602
‐ Hospitals make you sick
and keep you sick.

32:17.602 --> 32:19.062
No.

32:19.062 --> 32:22.858
Everything you're experiencing
comes from the withdrawal.

32:22.858 --> 32:25.944
You're safe here.

32:25.944 --> 32:28.655
Sam and I have your back.

32:28.655 --> 32:31.324
But if you feel the need
to leave,

32:31.324 --> 32:33.368
Sam will drive you.

32:33.368 --> 32:36.705
[chainsaw whirring]

32:36.705 --> 32:41.668
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:43.587 --> 32:46.590
[classical music ringtone
playing]

32:46.590 --> 32:50.760
♪ ♪

33:07.402 --> 33:09.154
SAM: Oh.

33:09.154 --> 33:13.283
Gosh darn it.
Just got a‐‐

33:13.283 --> 33:14.951
Hey.

33:14.951 --> 33:17.954
<i>[serene music]</i>

33:17.954 --> 33:24.085
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:24.085 --> 33:26.421
‐ If it's all right,

33:26.421 --> 33:28.340
I would like to stay
a little longer.

33:28.340 --> 33:34.137
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:34.137 --> 33:37.098
‐ You're right on the verge
of freeing yourself.

33:37.098 --> 33:40.518
Another few days,
you'll be right as rain.

33:40.518 --> 33:43.563
Come.
Help me with my herbs.

33:43.563 --> 33:45.482
This is what we did
this morning.

33:45.482 --> 33:48.026
You got to dry them all year.

33:48.026 --> 33:54.032
<i>♪ ♪</i>

33:55.283 --> 33:58.411
[tapping]

33:58.411 --> 34:02.290
[scratching]

34:02.290 --> 34:05.252
[reedy breathing]

34:11.299 --> 34:14.678
[scratching]

34:14.678 --> 34:19.015
[rattling breath]

34:19.015 --> 34:20.684
[scratching]

34:20.684 --> 34:22.686
[wheezing]

34:28.316 --> 34:31.319
[scratching and wheezing]

34:35.615 --> 34:38.952
[scratching increases]

34:47.919 --> 34:49.504
[wheezing]

34:49.504 --> 34:51.298
‐ [gasps]

34:52.716 --> 34:54.718
[sighs]

35:17.741 --> 35:20.744
[faint wheezing]

35:32.922 --> 35:35.258
[moaning]

35:35.258 --> 35:36.676
[panel clunks]

35:40.347 --> 35:44.309
[wheezing]

35:44.309 --> 35:48.229
[door creaks]

35:48.229 --> 35:51.232
<i>[ominous tone]</i>

35:51.232 --> 35:55.570
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:56.863 --> 35:58.490
[panel clunks]

35:58.490 --> 36:00.617
[wheezing]

36:00.617 --> 36:03.703
[scratching]

36:03.703 --> 36:06.831
[wood creaks]
[gasps]

36:06.831 --> 36:09.125
[sighs]

36:11.586 --> 36:14.214
[wheezing]

36:14.214 --> 36:18.343
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:18.343 --> 36:21.262
<i>[ominous rumbling building]</i>

36:21.262 --> 36:25.934
[wheezing]

36:34.484 --> 36:35.902
<i>[dramatic sting]</i>

36:35.902 --> 36:36.903
[yelps]

36:36.903 --> 36:39.406
‐ [wheezing]

36:39.406 --> 36:40.949
[knock on door]

36:40.949 --> 36:43.326
ELLIE: Jenna?
Are you all right, dear?

36:43.326 --> 36:44.369
‐ Yes, yes.
Sorry.

36:44.369 --> 36:46.037
Uh, bad dream.

36:46.037 --> 36:48.248
ELLIE: Can I get you anything?

36:48.248 --> 36:49.374
‐ No, I'm good.
Thank you.

36:49.374 --> 36:52.752
[classical music ringtone
playing]

36:52.752 --> 36:55.755
<i>[suspenseful music building]</i>

36:55.755 --> 37:02.762
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:21.197 --> 37:24.367
[screaming]
‐ [hissing]

37:24.367 --> 37:25.452
[knock on door]

37:25.452 --> 37:28.163
‐ Just open the door
and let me help.

37:28.163 --> 37:30.290
This is a critical time
for you, Jenna.

37:30.290 --> 37:32.459
You can't trust your senses.

37:32.459 --> 37:36.087
I need you to open this door.

37:36.087 --> 37:37.505
Jenna.

37:37.505 --> 37:42.969
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:42.969 --> 37:46.973
[door creaks]

37:46.973 --> 37:48.391
[grunts]

37:48.391 --> 37:51.978
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:51.978 --> 37:54.606
SAM: Ellie?

37:54.606 --> 37:56.107
Ellie‐May?

37:56.107 --> 37:59.360
Ellie!

37:59.360 --> 38:00.737
Are you all right?

38:00.737 --> 38:03.740
<i>[suspenseful music building]</i>

38:03.740 --> 38:08.995
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:08.995 --> 38:13.625
Ellie.

38:13.625 --> 38:14.959
You upstairs?

38:14.959 --> 38:18.046
Come, woman,
answer me.

38:18.046 --> 38:19.464
[door opens]

38:19.464 --> 38:26.471
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:40.235 --> 38:42.612
‐ [moans]
SAM: Oh, Lord, Ellie.

38:42.612 --> 38:44.697
What happened?
You're hurt.

38:44.697 --> 38:47.617
‐ She walloped me.

38:47.617 --> 38:49.244
‐ [softly]
Okay.

38:54.207 --> 38:56.334
<i>[dramatic sting]</i>
[screaming]

38:56.334 --> 38:59.671
[hissing and moaning]

38:59.671 --> 39:06.678
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:08.721 --> 39:11.724
[breathing heavily]

39:14.602 --> 39:15.770
Oh.
‐ Oh.

39:15.770 --> 39:20.567
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:20.567 --> 39:22.193
‐ Hey!

39:22.193 --> 39:29.200
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:33.204 --> 39:35.415
[wheezes]

39:35.415 --> 39:37.625
‐ There's nothing
to be afraid of here.

39:37.625 --> 39:39.836
No torment, no pain,

39:39.836 --> 39:42.297
no fear or anxiety.

39:42.297 --> 39:44.757
That's all over.

39:44.757 --> 39:46.718
Every member of this family,

39:46.718 --> 39:48.928
every single person
in this house

39:48.928 --> 39:50.930
is perfectly cared for

39:50.930 --> 39:53.850
by my natural painkillers
and nutrients.

39:53.850 --> 39:57.437
[moaning and scrabbling]

39:57.437 --> 39:59.939
Settle now.

39:59.939 --> 40:02.942
‐ [wheezes]
ELLIE: They're so excited
to meet you.

40:02.942 --> 40:04.777
‐ [whimpering]

40:04.777 --> 40:09.365
‐ I suppose I first heard
the calling at the hospital.

40:09.365 --> 40:14.162
All those poor, sick,
lonely people.

40:14.162 --> 40:17.624
I did what I could
to keep them from pain.

40:17.624 --> 40:18.958
It was all too clear

40:18.958 --> 40:22.253
that their fate was to die
a lonely death,

40:22.253 --> 40:23.713
in agony,

40:23.713 --> 40:27.133
surrounded by cold
and indifferent machines.

40:28.927 --> 40:32.263
But I could save them
from that fate.

40:32.263 --> 40:34.849
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

40:34.849 --> 40:37.894
I think the hospital knew
what I was doing.

40:37.894 --> 40:40.897
But they didn't want
anyone else to know.

40:40.897 --> 40:45.026
They gave me early retirement.

40:45.026 --> 40:49.113
Then the plant closed,
and Sam's work dried up, too.

40:49.113 --> 40:51.366
SAM: And right about that time,

40:51.366 --> 40:53.576
our daughter and her family

40:53.576 --> 40:55.453
threatened to move
out of the house.

40:55.453 --> 40:58.623
It was starting to feel like
maybe the saddest Thanksgiving

40:58.623 --> 41:00.416
of all time.

41:00.416 --> 41:01.376
Right back.

41:01.376 --> 41:03.127
‐ That's when it came to me,

41:03.127 --> 41:05.213
just as it did at the hospital.

41:05.213 --> 41:09.425
I knew how I could put together
all my love and knowledge,

41:09.425 --> 41:11.260
along with Sam's skills,

41:11.260 --> 41:14.097
and keep our family together...

41:14.097 --> 41:15.598
forever.

41:15.598 --> 41:18.601
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:18.601 --> 41:19.936
‐ [wheezing]

41:19.936 --> 41:21.896
<i>ELLIE:</i>
<i>Shiloh didn't mind.</i>

41:21.896 --> 41:24.440
I saw the relief in her eyes.

41:24.440 --> 41:28.152
Oh, that husband of hers
didn't like it, but‐‐

41:28.152 --> 41:30.238
‐ I took care of him okay.

41:30.238 --> 41:32.365
He was the first
of Ellie's weeds.

41:32.365 --> 41:34.409
‐ And the little ones,

41:34.409 --> 41:38.079
I rocked them in my arms
till it took hold.

41:38.079 --> 41:39.831
They didn't fuss at all

41:39.831 --> 41:44.210
when we relieved them
of their eyes and tongues.

41:44.210 --> 41:48.172
<i>Now we all live</i>
<i>under one roof.</i>

41:48.172 --> 41:49.924
<i>I tend the garden.</i>

41:49.924 --> 41:52.635
<i>Sam maintains the house.</i>

41:52.635 --> 41:54.887
<i>Life can be perfect</i>

41:54.887 --> 41:56.973
<i>when you don't ask</i>
<i>for too much.</i>

41:56.973 --> 42:00.226
<i>SAM: And this B&B thing,</i>
<i>we make enough to get by</i>

42:00.226 --> 42:03.646
<i>and keep the garden watered</i>
<i>and properly fed.</i>

42:03.646 --> 42:06.774
<i>ELLIE: Oh, and sometimes</i>
<i>it brings us something else‐‐</i>

42:06.774 --> 42:11.612
someone who needs our help.

42:11.612 --> 42:15.158
<i>Oh, I just can't look at one</i>
<i>of the Lord's little flowers,</i>

42:15.158 --> 42:16.701
<i>can't look 'em in the eye</i>

42:16.701 --> 42:20.246
<i>knowing what the cruel world</i>
<i>has in store for them.</i>

42:20.246 --> 42:21.372
<i>SAM: You know,</i>
<i>we measured you up</i>

42:21.372 --> 42:22.540
<i>the first night you were here?</i>

42:22.540 --> 42:24.042
<i>ELLIE: And watered you</i>

42:24.042 --> 42:27.837
with the first doses
of my special formula.

42:27.837 --> 42:31.049
<i>Gavin‐‐he's here, too.</i>

42:31.049 --> 42:33.676
<i>We helped him</i>
<i>plant some roots.</i>

42:33.676 --> 42:36.429
The two of you belong
together...

42:36.429 --> 42:38.014
with us.

42:38.014 --> 42:41.309
<i>♪ ♪</i>

42:41.309 --> 42:43.895
‐ [whimpers]

42:43.895 --> 42:46.105
‐ No, child.

42:46.105 --> 42:48.232
Don't fret.
‐ [whimpers]

42:48.232 --> 42:51.861
ELLIE: Just to make sure
there's no pain.

42:51.861 --> 42:53.696
‐ Ellie has
the kindest of ways.

42:53.696 --> 42:55.990
You won't feel a thing.

42:55.990 --> 42:58.367
‐ Just the relief
of not having to see,

42:58.367 --> 43:01.120
not having to weep anymore.

43:01.120 --> 43:02.330
‐ And guess what.

43:02.330 --> 43:05.041
I built you
the tiniest, comfiest place.

43:05.041 --> 43:08.252
The only problem we have there

43:08.252 --> 43:10.379
is the damn cockroaches

43:10.379 --> 43:13.132
will just keep nibbling away
at everything.

43:13.132 --> 43:14.300
‐ Hush, Sam.

43:14.300 --> 43:16.677
She doesn't need to think
about that now.

43:16.677 --> 43:18.554
‐ Oh, sorry.

43:18.554 --> 43:22.600
‐ All that awaits
is freedom forever

43:22.600 --> 43:25.019
from all the cruelties of life.

43:25.019 --> 43:29.690
<i>♪ ♪</i>

43:29.690 --> 43:36.239
[doorbell rings]

43:42.328 --> 43:44.163
Can I help you?

43:44.163 --> 43:47.708
‐ Um, have you, uh‐‐
have you seen this girl?

43:47.708 --> 43:50.628
I've been following her
for some time now.

43:50.628 --> 43:53.464
I'm at the motel,
and she isn't there.

43:53.464 --> 43:56.008
I think
she's been staying here.

43:56.008 --> 43:59.345
‐ Yes, she was, but she left
early this evening.

43:59.345 --> 44:01.806
‐ Are‐‐are you sure?

44:01.806 --> 44:05.226
I didn't see her leave.

44:05.226 --> 44:06.519
‐ [laughs]

44:06.519 --> 44:08.229
Why don't you come on in?

44:08.229 --> 44:09.939
We'll straighten all this out.

44:09.939 --> 44:11.566
‐ Thank you.

44:15.361 --> 44:17.196
[door closes]
ELLIE: Please.

44:17.196 --> 44:20.324
Sit here, Mr....
‐ Balsam.

44:20.324 --> 44:23.578
ELLIE: Well, Mr. Balsam,
you look exhausted.

44:23.578 --> 44:26.289
‐ You've got no idea
how tired I am.

44:26.289 --> 44:27.540
‐ You stay right here.

44:27.540 --> 44:30.585
I'm gonna bring you
a nice cup of hot tea.

44:30.585 --> 44:31.794
‐ Thank you.

44:33.504 --> 44:36.507
<i>[ominous music]</i>

44:36.507 --> 44:39.719
<i>♪ ♪</i>

44:39.719 --> 44:42.138
JENNA:
[whimpers]

44:42.138 --> 44:49.145
<i>♪ ♪</i>

45:02.700 --> 45:05.995
‐ There we go.

45:05.995 --> 45:08.998
‐ My son Tony.

45:08.998 --> 45:12.668
‐ Oh.
A very handsome young man.

45:12.668 --> 45:14.462
‐ He's a good boy.

45:14.462 --> 45:16.839
Wouldn't hurt a fly.

45:16.839 --> 45:18.633
He struggled
with depression a bit,

45:18.633 --> 45:20.551
but he's doing all right.

45:20.551 --> 45:22.261
We were so hopeful
when he told us

45:22.261 --> 45:24.889
that he met a girl
that he really liked,

45:24.889 --> 45:26.557
one that really understood him.

45:26.557 --> 45:29.560
A girl by the name
of Jenna Branson.

45:31.729 --> 45:33.564
Kids don't understand.

45:33.564 --> 45:35.608
They've got no sense
of proportion.

45:35.608 --> 45:38.569
Everything is huge...

45:38.569 --> 45:41.239
dramatic, apocalyptic.

45:41.239 --> 45:43.157
‐ It's a passionate time.

45:43.157 --> 45:44.367
They'll learn.

45:44.367 --> 45:46.369
Time's the teacher.

45:46.369 --> 45:48.287
‐ Tony didn't have time,

45:48.287 --> 45:49.664
not enough.

45:49.664 --> 45:54.252
The records show
that he was on the phone...

45:54.252 --> 45:55.836
with Jenna.

45:55.836 --> 45:58.673
‐ [gasps]

45:58.673 --> 46:00.299
BALSAM:
I just want to talk to her.

46:00.299 --> 46:04.303
<i>♪ ♪</i>

46:04.303 --> 46:06.973
‐ [grunts]

46:06.973 --> 46:14.021
<i>♪ ♪</i>

46:14.021 --> 46:16.941
‐ I'm not trying
to blame anyone.

46:16.941 --> 46:19.652
I just want to know.

46:19.652 --> 46:22.071
[grunts]

46:25.366 --> 46:27.785
‐ You took
your sweet fucking time.

46:27.785 --> 46:30.788
<i>[suspenseful music building]</i>

46:30.788 --> 46:34.417
<i>♪ ♪</i>

46:34.417 --> 46:36.002
‐ [grunts]

46:36.002 --> 46:43.009
<i>♪ ♪</i>

46:55.646 --> 46:57.857
‐ Bring his car around back
and be quick about it.

46:57.857 --> 47:04.864
<i>♪ ♪</i>

47:04.864 --> 47:07.867
‐ [grunting]

47:07.867 --> 47:14.874
<i>♪ ♪</i>

47:22.506 --> 47:25.301
[yelps]

47:25.301 --> 47:28.304
[groaning]

47:28.304 --> 47:35.311
<i>♪ ♪</i>

47:41.108 --> 47:44.320
[engine revving]

47:44.320 --> 47:51.327
<i>♪ ♪</i>

48:00.127 --> 48:03.130
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

48:03.130 --> 48:10.137
<i>♪ ♪</i>

48:31.700 --> 48:33.494
[car beeping]

48:33.494 --> 48:35.371
SAM: I'll take him out
to the quarry‐‐

48:35.371 --> 48:38.666
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

48:38.666 --> 48:41.502
We'll get her back
sometime soon, okay?

48:41.502 --> 48:48.509
<i>♪ ♪</i>

48:54.223 --> 48:57.059
Okay.

48:57.059 --> 48:58.561
ELLIE: Let's go.
Help me.

48:58.561 --> 49:00.104
Get his legs.

49:00.104 --> 49:03.065
[both grunting]
SAM: He's huge.

49:03.065 --> 49:07.319
<i>♪ ♪</i>

49:07.319 --> 49:08.446
All right?

49:08.446 --> 49:11.031
<i>♪ ♪</i>

49:11.031 --> 49:12.366
[car door opens]

49:12.366 --> 49:14.118
What are we gonna do
about Jenna?

49:14.118 --> 49:16.954
ELLIE: She's going nowhere.
We'll finish with her later‐‐

49:16.954 --> 49:18.581
after the weeding.

49:18.581 --> 49:24.128
<i>♪ ♪</i>

49:24.128 --> 49:27.131
[engine turns over]

49:27.131 --> 49:34.138
<i>♪ ♪</i>

50:19.808 --> 50:22.811
<i>[ominous music]</i>

50:22.811 --> 50:29.693
<i>♪ ♪</i>

50:50.548 --> 50:54.635
<i>[dramatic sting]</i>

50:54.635 --> 50:57.304
‐ [grunts]

50:57.304 --> 51:00.516
[engine idling]

51:00.516 --> 51:03.143
[engine revving]

51:03.143 --> 51:09.900
<i>♪ ♪</i>

51:20.452 --> 51:23.706
‐ [screaming]

51:23.706 --> 51:26.292
[metal and glass crashing]

51:36.218 --> 51:39.221
<i>[eerie music]</i>

51:39.221 --> 51:46.228
<i>♪ ♪</i>

51:55.779 --> 51:58.782
<i>[ominous music]</i>

51:58.782 --> 52:05.789
<i>♪ ♪</i>

52:15.299 --> 52:18.302
[inhuman screeching]

52:18.302 --> 52:25.225
<i>♪ ♪</i>

52:25.225 --> 52:27.978
[static crackling]

52:30.356 --> 52:32.191
[distorted voice]

52:32.191 --> 52:35.194
[voices whispering]

52:35.194 --> 52:42.201
<i>♪ ♪</i>

52:48.248 --> 52:50.626
[VCR whirs]

53:01.804 --> 53:03.180
MARY:
Where did this come from?

53:03.180 --> 53:04.848
STUDENT: There was just
an envelope by your door

53:04.848 --> 53:06.433
when I got here this morning.

53:06.433 --> 53:09.353
‐ Throw it away.

53:09.353 --> 53:10.646
[door closes]

53:10.646 --> 53:13.774
"That tape was
my first introduction to Simon.

53:13.774 --> 53:15.401
"He embodied
everything I despised,

53:15.401 --> 53:17.820
"all the pitiless parasites
who take advantage of people

53:17.820 --> 53:19.363
"at their most vulnerable,

53:19.363 --> 53:23.742
"but from the moment I met him,
I sensed there was...

53:23.742 --> 53:27.162
there was something
very different about Simon."

53:29.373 --> 53:32.376
"But first...

53:32.376 --> 53:34.545
I set out, quite frankly,
to destroy him."

53:34.545 --> 53:36.505
[laughter]

53:36.505 --> 53:38.549
‐ So love at first sight, then.

53:38.549 --> 53:40.384
‐ I'd say more like hate.

53:40.384 --> 53:42.177
‐ Yeah.
I can confirm that.

53:42.177 --> 53:44.179
[laughter]

53:44.179 --> 53:46.598
‐ Your book is
really all about Miles.

53:46.598 --> 53:48.851
I know it's hard, but can you
talk about your son?

53:48.851 --> 53:50.561
His last few days?

53:50.561 --> 53:53.605
<i>[somber music]</i>

53:53.605 --> 53:56.442
<i>♪ ♪</i>

53:56.442 --> 54:00.112
<i>MARY: I was alone with Miles</i>
<i>when he came into the world,</i>

54:00.112 --> 54:03.073
<i>and I was alone with him</i>
<i>when he left.</i>

54:03.073 --> 54:04.658
‐ You know what?
I'm his father.

54:04.658 --> 54:06.827
He's my son, too.
‐ You're not his father.

54:06.827 --> 54:08.162
You're just a man
who walked out

54:08.162 --> 54:10.205
because I refused to have
an abortion.

54:10.205 --> 54:14.001
‐ Yeah, well, I'm here now.

54:14.001 --> 54:16.837
‐ My God, you're drunk.

54:16.837 --> 54:20.132
‐ Well, I'm handling this
my own way.

54:20.132 --> 54:21.383
‐ Get out of my sight.

54:26.180 --> 54:29.057
[door closes]

54:29.057 --> 54:31.351
MILES: You, Mom?
MARY: Hey, Miles.

54:37.107 --> 54:38.525
How you doing?

54:38.525 --> 54:40.277
‐ Good.

54:40.277 --> 54:43.280
‐ Can I get you anything?

54:43.280 --> 54:47.284
‐ Mom.
MARY: Mm‐hmm?

54:47.284 --> 54:50.245
‐ Where do you think we go...

54:50.245 --> 54:51.955
after we die?

54:54.875 --> 54:57.419
‐ Um...

54:57.419 --> 55:00.422
well, I think that we just...

55:02.799 --> 55:04.968
We just go to sleep, you know?

55:07.304 --> 55:10.015
‐ That's all right.

55:10.015 --> 55:13.602
I'm awfully tired.

55:13.602 --> 55:16.813
‐ Where do you want to go?

55:16.813 --> 55:18.232
‐ With you.

55:18.232 --> 55:21.860
I just want to be with you.

55:21.860 --> 55:23.487
‐ Close your eyes.

55:23.487 --> 55:27.366
<i>♪ ♪</i>

55:27.366 --> 55:29.952
[smooching]

55:29.952 --> 55:32.704
Love you very, very, very much.

55:32.704 --> 55:34.331
‐ I love you.

55:34.331 --> 55:39.378
<i>♪ ♪</i>

55:39.378 --> 55:43.840
<i>MARY: I was like a fish</i>
<i>trying to survive on air.</i>

55:43.840 --> 55:45.676
<i>But then it all changed.</i>

55:45.676 --> 55:52.683
<i>♪ ♪</i>

56:06.989 --> 56:09.491
‐ Hi.

56:09.491 --> 56:11.326
‐ What are you doing?

56:11.326 --> 56:12.619
‐ I was just saying hello.

56:12.619 --> 56:14.246
‐ No, what are you doing
in my office?

56:14.246 --> 56:15.414
Who let you in?

56:15.414 --> 56:18.667
‐ Which one do you want me
to answer first?

56:18.667 --> 56:20.586
‐ What?

56:20.586 --> 56:23.839
‐ Who am I, who let me in,
what am I doing here?

56:23.839 --> 56:27.801
‐ Can you please leave?

56:27.801 --> 56:29.886
‐ I thought
this was your office hours.

56:29.886 --> 56:32.639
‐ You're a student?

56:32.639 --> 56:34.600
‐ Of life.

56:34.600 --> 56:35.684
‐ Right, you either leave,

56:35.684 --> 56:37.394
or I'm calling
the campus police.

56:37.394 --> 56:39.896
‐ And have me arrested?
For doing what?

56:39.896 --> 56:41.189
For daring to disturb

56:41.189 --> 56:44.109
the famous
Professor Mary Florensky?

56:44.109 --> 56:46.486
I do dare, apparently.
[bell tolls outside]

56:46.486 --> 56:49.990
Professor, this is
not so much a profession for me

56:49.990 --> 56:52.618
but a calling, a vocation.

56:52.618 --> 56:55.704
‐ And what exactly is
your calling?

56:55.704 --> 56:57.539
‐ I'm a speaker for the dead.

57:01.209 --> 57:03.795
You see my tape?

57:03.795 --> 57:05.881
‐ That was you?

57:05.881 --> 57:09.676
Well, you're either a magician,
or you're mentally ill.

57:09.676 --> 57:13.263
‐ [chuckles]

57:13.263 --> 57:14.890
I did go crazy there
for a while

57:14.890 --> 57:17.684
while I was refusing
my calling.

57:17.684 --> 57:21.938
I tried
every numbing agent possible.

57:21.938 --> 57:23.023
I'm still in recovery.

57:23.023 --> 57:25.525
I always will be,
they say, but...

57:25.525 --> 57:28.779
other than that,
I'm deeply and tragically sane.

57:28.779 --> 57:30.739
‐ Or a glutton for punishment.

57:30.739 --> 57:32.282
You do know what it is I do?

57:32.282 --> 57:33.367
‐ Yes.
Yes.

57:33.367 --> 57:35.118
You expose frauds.

57:35.118 --> 57:36.745
You publicly humiliate them.

57:36.745 --> 57:38.622
I've read your books.

57:38.622 --> 57:39.831
I've seen you on TV,

57:39.831 --> 57:41.625
and, quite frankly,
you are no fun.

57:41.625 --> 57:43.210
‐ Neither are frauds.

57:43.210 --> 57:44.503
‐ Why is it so important

57:44.503 --> 57:46.922
that you convince everybody
it's all bullshit?

57:46.922 --> 57:49.383
Who are you really trying
to convince‐‐yourself?

57:49.383 --> 57:50.676
‐ Right, time's up.
I'm very busy.

57:50.676 --> 57:54.262
Now leave, or I am calling
the campus police.

57:54.262 --> 57:55.722
‐ Professor,
I don't want to be here

57:55.722 --> 57:57.766
any more than you want me here.

57:57.766 --> 57:59.893
‐ Good.
We agree.

57:59.893 --> 58:01.353
Now leave.

58:03.772 --> 58:05.482
SIMON:
I can't do that.

58:05.482 --> 58:06.817
‐ And why is that?

58:06.817 --> 58:08.527
‐ Because Miles sent me here.

58:10.445 --> 58:14.241
<i>MARY: Science was once defined</i>
<i>as putting nature to the rack,</i>

58:14.241 --> 58:16.535
and I guess, in a way,
that's what I did with Simon.

58:16.535 --> 58:19.705
I tested him every way,
everywhere I could.

58:19.705 --> 58:22.374
‐ So from skeptic to believer?

58:22.374 --> 58:24.084
‐ Believer?

58:24.084 --> 58:26.044
No.

58:26.044 --> 58:28.547
Faith is believing in things
that you can't see,

58:28.547 --> 58:31.508
but I saw what Simon can do.

58:31.508 --> 58:34.511
‐ Well, it's not me
that does anything.

58:34.511 --> 58:36.012
‐ Oh...

58:36.012 --> 58:39.766
All right,
what comes through him.

58:39.766 --> 58:42.310
I challenge any of you to...

58:42.310 --> 58:44.396
to witness
one of Simon's convocations

58:44.396 --> 58:47.023
and remain unchanged.

58:47.023 --> 58:48.442
<i>[ominous sting]</i>

58:48.442 --> 58:51.153
All right, our subject today
is Simon McNeal.

58:51.153 --> 58:52.404
He's 28 years old.

58:52.404 --> 58:54.322
In addition to being
a charming narcissist,

58:54.322 --> 58:56.158
he's also
a self‐professed medium.

58:56.158 --> 58:58.785
Today we'll put those claims
to the test.

59:14.968 --> 59:18.805
So, as you can see,
the room is bare.

59:18.805 --> 59:21.558
Simon, too.
Arms.

59:50.962 --> 59:53.590
‐ [whispering]
He's almost here.

59:53.590 --> 59:56.593
<i>[ominous music]</i>

59:56.593 --> 1:00:03.600
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:00:04.726 --> 1:00:06.061
‐ For those of you
that don't know,

1:00:06.061 --> 1:00:08.522
I've recently lost my son Miles
to leukemia.

1:00:08.522 --> 1:00:09.815
He was 7 years old.

1:00:09.815 --> 1:00:13.109
This is what people like Simon
like to prey on‐‐

1:00:13.109 --> 1:00:15.237
grief.

1:00:15.237 --> 1:00:19.491
So today we're gonna make
an example of him.

1:00:19.491 --> 1:00:22.869
All right, Simon,
can you hear us?

1:00:22.869 --> 1:00:25.539
We're ready for your miracles
whenever you are.

1:00:27.374 --> 1:00:29.543
‐ You're all gonna hear
some very disturbing sounds.

1:00:29.543 --> 1:00:31.294
That's part of the convocation.

1:00:31.294 --> 1:00:32.963
But no matter what you hear,

1:00:32.963 --> 1:00:35.173
that door must stay closed.

1:00:38.552 --> 1:00:41.555
Mary, I've accepted
your controls

1:00:41.555 --> 1:00:44.474
and your precautions,

1:00:44.474 --> 1:00:46.518
but I need complete darkness.

1:00:48.895 --> 1:00:50.397
Or rather, they do.

1:00:52.399 --> 1:00:55.110
‐ "They"?
‐ The dead.

1:00:55.110 --> 1:00:58.572
[electricity crackles]

1:00:58.572 --> 1:01:01.575
[screaming]

1:01:01.575 --> 1:01:04.578
<i>[eerie music]</i>

1:01:04.578 --> 1:01:09.207
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:01:09.207 --> 1:01:10.750
[static crackling]

1:01:10.750 --> 1:01:14.921
[inhuman screeching]

1:01:14.921 --> 1:01:17.924
[distorted screaming]

1:01:17.924 --> 1:01:20.677
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:01:20.677 --> 1:01:23.346
[static crackling]

1:01:23.346 --> 1:01:24.347
[distorted moan]

1:01:29.561 --> 1:01:31.563
‐ Simon, can you hear us?

1:01:33.148 --> 1:01:34.774
Simon?

1:01:38.194 --> 1:01:40.488
<i>[dramatic sting]</i>

1:01:40.488 --> 1:01:42.866
[inhuman screech]

1:01:44.743 --> 1:01:47.746
SIMON: [breathing heavily]

1:01:50.123 --> 1:01:51.583
MARY:
Hey, hey.

1:01:51.583 --> 1:01:52.751
It's okay.
It's all right.

1:01:52.751 --> 1:01:54.586
Can you call a medic?
STUDENT: Yeah.

1:01:54.586 --> 1:01:56.880
‐ It's okay, Simon.
Breathe.

1:01:56.880 --> 1:02:00.634
<i>[ominous music]</i>

1:02:00.634 --> 1:02:07.641
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:02:07.641 --> 1:02:11.770
<i>[dramatic sting]</i>

1:02:11.770 --> 1:02:14.689
[siren wailing]

1:02:14.689 --> 1:02:18.568
<i>[indistinct radio chatter]</i>

1:02:18.568 --> 1:02:21.196
What happened back there?

1:02:21.196 --> 1:02:22.948
‐ I just let them speak.

1:02:24.950 --> 1:02:27.494
I let him speak.

1:02:27.494 --> 1:02:29.245
‐ It's not possible.

1:02:29.245 --> 1:02:31.831
‐ Oh, Mary.

1:02:31.831 --> 1:02:33.458
You aren't ready.

1:02:36.294 --> 1:02:39.673
‐ I need to know
what happened back there.

1:02:39.673 --> 1:02:41.633
‐ You aren't ready, Mary.

1:02:41.633 --> 1:02:43.635
‐ What happened?

1:02:43.635 --> 1:02:45.303
‐ Ma'am.

1:02:45.303 --> 1:02:47.138
Please.

1:02:47.138 --> 1:02:50.141
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

1:02:50.141 --> 1:02:57.190
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:03:11.830 --> 1:03:14.833
‐ He's not in there, you know.

1:03:14.833 --> 1:03:17.085
Not the real him.

1:03:17.085 --> 1:03:19.754
That's just some old clothes
he's grown out of.

1:03:19.754 --> 1:03:22.298
‐ I see you've recovered.

1:03:22.298 --> 1:03:24.926
‐ I see you haven't.
‐ No, I haven't.

1:03:24.926 --> 1:03:27.262
I can't stop thinking
about him.

1:03:29.055 --> 1:03:32.100
SIMON:
Is that why you asked me here?

1:03:32.100 --> 1:03:34.519
‐ Assumptions must be tempered
by an open mind

1:03:34.519 --> 1:03:37.147
to new evidence.

1:03:37.147 --> 1:03:39.441
The best scientists
always question.

1:03:42.527 --> 1:03:45.822
I'm willing to have
my mind opened...

1:03:45.822 --> 1:03:47.991
by you.

1:03:47.991 --> 1:03:49.826
‐ I'm telling you,

1:03:49.826 --> 1:03:52.328
he's not in there.

1:03:52.328 --> 1:03:53.997
‐ Then where is he?

1:04:57.060 --> 1:05:04.109
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:05:42.105 --> 1:05:44.816
‐ He just wants to be near you.

1:05:44.816 --> 1:05:47.110
‐ That's what he said...

1:05:47.110 --> 1:05:50.029
his very last words to me.

1:05:50.029 --> 1:05:52.448
‐ He's so much closer
than you realize.

1:05:58.788 --> 1:06:00.456
No, I'm okay.

1:06:02.458 --> 1:06:04.127
‐ Sorry.

1:06:04.127 --> 1:06:06.004
I forgot.

1:06:06.004 --> 1:06:07.130
‐ Don't be.

1:06:07.130 --> 1:06:09.090
I'm a better man on the wagon.

1:06:09.090 --> 1:06:11.551
I've fallen off enough times
to know.

1:06:13.011 --> 1:06:15.013
MARY: Why would my son come
to you and not me?

1:06:15.013 --> 1:06:16.431
I'm his mother.

1:06:18.766 --> 1:06:21.060
I don't understand.
I need to understand.

1:06:21.060 --> 1:06:24.731
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:06:24.731 --> 1:06:26.065
Please.

1:06:28.109 --> 1:06:31.821
‐ Once upon a time,
we were wanderers.

1:06:31.821 --> 1:06:35.909
And long before we ever built
a permanent home for ourselves,

1:06:35.909 --> 1:06:37.952
we built homes for our dead,

1:06:37.952 --> 1:06:40.288
places we'd return to
in our wanderings,

1:06:40.288 --> 1:06:44.626
to rest,
to recover, to honor them.

1:06:44.626 --> 1:06:46.127
And then as we stopped
our wanderings,

1:06:46.127 --> 1:06:48.713
we stopped building new homes.

1:06:48.713 --> 1:06:51.341
We moved in with our dead.

1:06:51.341 --> 1:06:54.469
We buried them beneath us
as we continued to honor them

1:06:54.469 --> 1:06:57.597
and be protected and nurtured
by them.

1:06:57.597 --> 1:07:02.393
But as time passed,
our conception of them changed.

1:07:02.393 --> 1:07:05.438
We began to fear them.

1:07:05.438 --> 1:07:09.943
And in that fear,
we banished them...

1:07:09.943 --> 1:07:11.986
from the homes
to the churchyard

1:07:11.986 --> 1:07:14.155
and then farther...

1:07:14.155 --> 1:07:16.616
to outside the city walls.

1:07:16.616 --> 1:07:20.995
Step by step, we exiled them
to their highway,

1:07:20.995 --> 1:07:24.374
leaving them homeless
and voiceless.

1:07:24.374 --> 1:07:26.417
They want their stories
to be told.

1:07:26.417 --> 1:07:29.045
They want their voices
to be heard.

1:07:31.256 --> 1:07:34.926
They want to be close
to those they love the most...

1:07:34.926 --> 1:07:36.803
like your son.

1:07:39.222 --> 1:07:41.641
‐ My son exists
only in my memory.

1:07:44.018 --> 1:07:48.606
‐ Didn't he leave you
a message?

1:07:48.606 --> 1:07:52.610
‐ Whatever happened that day,
it doesn't prove anything.

1:07:55.738 --> 1:07:58.992
‐ Miles sent me to you
for a reason, Mary.

1:07:58.992 --> 1:08:03.454
Because if you,
with all your tools of science,

1:08:03.454 --> 1:08:06.416
with all your certainty,
if you fail to prove me wrong,

1:08:06.416 --> 1:08:09.043
it will change the world.

1:08:09.043 --> 1:08:11.504
And at that point,

1:08:11.504 --> 1:08:15.133
you will see how close
your son really is to you.

1:08:15.133 --> 1:08:22.140
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:08:58.009 --> 1:09:01.929
<i>[ominous music]</i>

1:09:01.929 --> 1:09:06.184
‐ [gasps, breathing heavily]

1:09:06.184 --> 1:09:09.395
<i>Simon knew things</i>
<i>that no one else could know,</i>

1:09:09.395 --> 1:09:11.481
<i>and through him,</i>
<i>Miles sent me messages</i>

1:09:11.481 --> 1:09:14.192
<i>that couldn't be</i>
<i>from anyone else.</i>

1:09:14.192 --> 1:09:16.694
<i>I guess that's why</i>
<i>I fell in love with him.</i>

1:09:16.694 --> 1:09:20.323
<i>It's almost like Miles</i>
<i>was giving me permission.</i>

1:09:20.323 --> 1:09:22.116
<i>A year later,</i>
<i>I can still feel my son</i>

1:09:22.116 --> 1:09:23.618
<i>everywhere I go.</i>

1:09:23.618 --> 1:09:24.911
And then I began to realize

1:09:24.911 --> 1:09:28.498
that this wasn't just about me
and my son.

1:09:28.498 --> 1:09:29.957
It was about all of us.

1:09:29.957 --> 1:09:34.170
I mean, what if scientists were
the ones acting on faith

1:09:34.170 --> 1:09:36.130
instead of using
our best resources

1:09:36.130 --> 1:09:38.549
to find the truth?

1:09:38.549 --> 1:09:41.427
We have the ability
to study quantum objects

1:09:41.427 --> 1:09:45.431
a billion times smaller
than an atom to...

1:09:45.431 --> 1:09:48.726
the largest structure
there is‐‐the universe itself.

1:09:48.726 --> 1:09:51.229
And that's why we started
this foundation.

1:09:51.229 --> 1:09:52.855
With your financial support,

1:09:52.855 --> 1:09:55.274
we would have access
to the best imaging power

1:09:55.274 --> 1:09:57.485
science has to offer.

1:09:57.485 --> 1:09:59.487
Simon has a great quote for it.

1:09:59.487 --> 1:10:00.822
‐ Yes.

1:10:00.822 --> 1:10:05.368
"The horizon is just the limits
of our vision."

1:10:05.368 --> 1:10:06.953
‐ Isn't he something?

1:10:06.953 --> 1:10:10.581
You have no idea
what he's capable of.

1:10:10.581 --> 1:10:17.547
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:10:27.181 --> 1:10:29.392
What are you doing?

1:10:29.392 --> 1:10:31.269
‐ Oh, fuck.

1:10:34.564 --> 1:10:36.566
‐ I'm so sorry, Professor.

1:10:40.528 --> 1:10:42.321
‐ You want to stop looking
at me like that?

1:10:42.321 --> 1:10:43.948
MARY: Like what?

1:10:43.948 --> 1:10:46.325
‐ Like I just shot
your fucking dog.

1:10:46.325 --> 1:10:50.413
‐ Explain yourself.

1:10:50.413 --> 1:10:51.998
‐ Can it wait till I'm sober?

1:10:51.998 --> 1:10:53.708
MARY: No.
Now.

1:10:53.708 --> 1:10:58.212
‐ Well, I think the crime scene
speaks for itself, no?

1:10:58.212 --> 1:11:00.423
‐ This isn't you, Simon.

1:11:00.423 --> 1:11:01.507
‐ What if it is?

1:11:01.507 --> 1:11:03.718
What if this is
exactly who I am?

1:11:03.718 --> 1:11:06.179
‐ Don't do that.
No.

1:11:06.179 --> 1:11:07.889
Simon.

1:11:07.889 --> 1:11:09.724
I know you.

1:11:09.724 --> 1:11:11.809
‐ You don't know me.
You haven't got a fucking clue.

1:11:11.809 --> 1:11:13.895
‐ You're in recovery,

1:11:13.895 --> 1:11:16.063
and this is part
of the struggle with your gift.

1:11:16.063 --> 1:11:18.357
‐ What you don't know...

1:11:18.357 --> 1:11:20.151
is that's where I met your ex.

1:11:22.612 --> 1:11:26.282
I was his sponsor
in the program.

1:11:26.282 --> 1:11:29.160
He told me
all about your dying son.

1:11:31.913 --> 1:11:34.123
‐ What do you‐‐

1:11:34.123 --> 1:11:36.918
No, what are you saying?

1:11:38.795 --> 1:11:42.048
No.
You answer me!

1:11:42.048 --> 1:11:43.591
‐ I was small‐time, Mary.

1:11:43.591 --> 1:11:45.510
You helped me go big‐time.

1:11:45.510 --> 1:11:48.012
But investors‐‐that's
another story completely.

1:11:48.012 --> 1:11:49.180
I've been to prison.

1:11:49.180 --> 1:11:51.682
I have no interest
in going back there.

1:11:51.682 --> 1:11:54.352
You don't fuck with people
with money.

1:11:54.352 --> 1:11:55.812
You understand me?

1:11:55.812 --> 1:11:58.731
They don't take lightly
to being conned.

1:11:58.731 --> 1:12:00.233
‐ What con?

1:12:00.233 --> 1:12:02.735
‐ Oh, Mary, wake the fuck up.

1:12:02.735 --> 1:12:06.030
It was a con.
It was all a con.

1:12:06.030 --> 1:12:07.365
‐ No.
That's impossible.

1:12:07.365 --> 1:12:08.991
You couldn't fake that.
I was there.

1:12:08.991 --> 1:12:11.285
‐ That first time in the lab,
I rigged it.

1:12:11.285 --> 1:12:13.412
I paid a maintenance guy
to cut the power.

1:12:13.412 --> 1:12:15.540
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:12:15.540 --> 1:12:17.291
<i>And the messages from beyond?</i>

1:12:17.291 --> 1:12:19.460
<i>I wrote those</i>
<i>the night before.</i>

1:12:19.460 --> 1:12:20.962
<i>I used phenolphthalein.</i>

1:12:20.962 --> 1:12:24.257
<i>It's invisible until exposed</i>
<i>to an activating agent‐‐</i>

1:12:24.257 --> 1:12:26.467
<i>in this case, simple ammonia.</i>

1:12:26.467 --> 1:12:30.513
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:12:30.513 --> 1:12:34.934
[distorted screams]

1:12:34.934 --> 1:12:36.686
<i>Oh, and the seizures?</i>

1:12:36.686 --> 1:12:39.105
<i>That was a microdose</i>
<i>of penicillin.</i>

1:12:39.105 --> 1:12:40.106
<i>I'm allergic to it.</i>

1:12:40.106 --> 1:12:41.315
<i>Takes an hour to kick in</i>

1:12:41.315 --> 1:12:44.819
and makes the drama
all the more convincing.

1:12:44.819 --> 1:12:47.405
You fell for it, Mary,
but you fell too hard.

1:12:47.405 --> 1:12:50.283
I tried to slow things down,
but you were obsessed.

1:12:50.283 --> 1:12:52.243
This ends here and now.

1:12:52.243 --> 1:12:54.453
Your son is dead.
He's gone.

1:12:54.453 --> 1:12:56.789
He's six feet under.

1:12:59.750 --> 1:13:01.377
‐ Fucking piece of shit.

1:13:01.377 --> 1:13:02.628
‐ For what, Mary?

1:13:02.628 --> 1:13:04.422
For telling people
what they want to hear?

1:13:04.422 --> 1:13:06.299
For giving them closure?

1:13:06.299 --> 1:13:08.301
‐ You fucking drunk!

1:13:11.178 --> 1:13:13.347
SIMON:
Just remember something.

1:13:13.347 --> 1:13:14.348
No one's gonna believe

1:13:14.348 --> 1:13:16.434
that you're not in this
with me.

1:13:16.434 --> 1:13:18.436
So, if I'm going to jail,
you're going with me.

1:13:18.436 --> 1:13:20.897
‐ [breathing heavily]

1:13:49.050 --> 1:13:52.053
[chalk squeaking and scraping]

1:13:58.351 --> 1:14:04.732
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:14:04.732 --> 1:14:05.942
[bedsprings squeak]

1:14:05.942 --> 1:14:08.945
[labored breathing]

1:14:08.945 --> 1:14:15.952
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:14:25.294 --> 1:14:28.297
<i>[dark music]</i>

1:14:28.297 --> 1:14:35.304
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:14:53.030 --> 1:14:56.033
[swing squeaking]

1:15:12.925 --> 1:15:17.179
‐ I'm not entirely sure
what I said last night.

1:15:17.179 --> 1:15:19.432
Uh, I blacked out,

1:15:19.432 --> 1:15:22.268
which isn't surprising.

1:15:22.268 --> 1:15:24.270
When you haven't fallen off
the wagon in a while,

1:15:24.270 --> 1:15:26.647
sometimes it can be
a pretty big fall.

1:15:26.647 --> 1:15:29.442
‐ I get it.

1:15:29.442 --> 1:15:32.611
‐ Right, so what did I say?
‐ You told me the truth.

1:15:34.405 --> 1:15:37.116
‐ Yeah, I was afraid of that.
Um, I'm gonna grab my stuff.

1:15:37.116 --> 1:15:39.035
‐ Why?
Where are you going?

1:15:40.870 --> 1:15:43.122
‐ I don't know.
Uh, not here.

1:15:43.122 --> 1:15:44.832
I assume
you don't want me here.

1:15:44.832 --> 1:15:48.377
‐ You're not going anywhere.
We have a lot of work to do.

1:15:48.377 --> 1:15:51.672
‐ What do you mean "we"?

1:15:51.672 --> 1:15:53.966
‐ Maybe I knew all along.

1:15:53.966 --> 1:15:56.427
Hmm.

1:15:56.427 --> 1:15:58.012
But that doesn't matter now.

1:15:58.012 --> 1:16:01.307
This is much bigger
than you and me.

1:16:01.307 --> 1:16:03.517
‐ I'm sorry.
I'm not understanding.

1:16:03.517 --> 1:16:06.020
‐ The show must go on.

1:16:08.147 --> 1:16:10.441
There's a lot of money
on the table.

1:16:10.441 --> 1:16:13.027
We still have investors
coming tonight.

1:16:13.027 --> 1:16:14.862
Go get yourself cleaned up.

1:16:14.862 --> 1:16:17.239
Go on.

1:16:18.783 --> 1:16:23.329
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:16:23.329 --> 1:16:26.916
[laughs]

1:16:26.916 --> 1:16:29.460
We're inviting you to become
part of a Manhattan Project

1:16:29.460 --> 1:16:32.088
to see over the horizon

1:16:32.088 --> 1:16:34.840
that separates life from death.

1:16:34.840 --> 1:16:38.469
[crowd murmurs excitedly]
The real final frontier.

1:16:40.221 --> 1:16:41.847
Are you ready, my love?

1:16:43.265 --> 1:16:45.184
‐ Ready.

1:16:45.184 --> 1:16:46.644
‐ You're all in
for a real treat.

1:16:46.644 --> 1:16:48.020
[man chuckles]

1:16:48.020 --> 1:16:51.148
Simon has agreed to perform
a convocation tonight.

1:16:51.148 --> 1:16:52.900
So, if you'd like
to come upstairs,

1:16:52.900 --> 1:16:55.528
you can witness
what Simon can do.

1:16:55.528 --> 1:16:58.531
Come.
[crowd chatters excitedly]

1:16:58.531 --> 1:17:02.159
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:17:02.159 --> 1:17:04.161
‐ What the fuck are you doing?

1:17:06.330 --> 1:17:09.041
‐ Just play along.

1:17:09.041 --> 1:17:10.626
You'll see.

1:17:10.626 --> 1:17:17.633
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:18:17.735 --> 1:18:20.362
[whispering] You know,
you really pissed them off.

1:18:20.362 --> 1:18:27.369
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:18:39.757 --> 1:18:43.302
Now, you are gonna hear
some very disturbing noises,

1:18:43.302 --> 1:18:44.553
but you mustn't be concerned.

1:18:44.553 --> 1:18:46.889
It's all part
of the convocation.

1:18:46.889 --> 1:18:48.724
The dead have highways,

1:18:48.724 --> 1:18:51.268
and Simon creates an opening,

1:18:51.268 --> 1:18:53.479
an exit, so to speak.

1:18:53.479 --> 1:18:57.066
No matter what happens,
no matter what we hear,

1:18:57.066 --> 1:19:00.152
we mustn't open the door.

1:19:00.152 --> 1:19:02.112
Isn't that right, Simon?

1:19:02.112 --> 1:19:05.115
[rocking chair creaking]

1:19:14.959 --> 1:19:17.253
MILES: [whispering eerily]
We're not sleeping.

1:19:23.259 --> 1:19:25.761
<i>[suspenseful sting]</i>

1:19:25.761 --> 1:19:29.056
<i>[eerie rumbling]</i>

1:19:29.056 --> 1:19:32.059
[voices whispering]

1:19:38.107 --> 1:19:40.484
[screaming]

1:19:40.484 --> 1:19:43.487
[voices whispering]

1:19:44.905 --> 1:19:46.657
‐ What the fuck is this?

1:19:46.657 --> 1:19:50.661
[voices whispering]

1:19:56.208 --> 1:19:58.544
Mary!
Save me!

1:19:58.544 --> 1:19:59.712
[screaming]

1:19:59.712 --> 1:20:01.088
[crunching and cracking]

1:20:01.088 --> 1:20:04.508
[screaming]

1:20:04.508 --> 1:20:07.094
What the fuck is happening
to me?

1:20:07.094 --> 1:20:08.971
‐ It's very disturbing
how he suffers

1:20:08.971 --> 1:20:10.723
to communicate with the beyond.

1:20:10.723 --> 1:20:12.558
SIMON: Mary, let me
the fuck out of here!

1:20:12.558 --> 1:20:15.019
‐ But we mustn't interfere.

1:20:15.019 --> 1:20:18.063
[voices whispering]

1:20:20.107 --> 1:20:23.110
SIMON:
[screaming]

1:20:23.110 --> 1:20:24.903
<i>[eerie music]</i>

1:20:24.903 --> 1:20:26.405
[inhuman shrieking]

1:20:26.405 --> 1:20:29.408
[voices whispering]

1:20:29.408 --> 1:20:33.120
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:20:33.120 --> 1:20:34.663
[screaming]

1:20:34.663 --> 1:20:37.791
[voices whispering]

1:20:37.791 --> 1:20:41.420
[screaming]

1:20:41.420 --> 1:20:48.427
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:20:52.139 --> 1:20:54.933
[screaming]

1:20:54.933 --> 1:21:01.982
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:21:04.860 --> 1:21:08.614
[voices stop,
electricity crackles]

1:21:13.494 --> 1:21:16.497
[wind whistling]

1:21:27.007 --> 1:21:28.092
[door creaks]

1:21:28.092 --> 1:21:31.095
[wheezing]

1:21:31.095 --> 1:21:34.098
<i>[ominous music]</i>

1:21:34.098 --> 1:21:39.353
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:21:39.353 --> 1:21:42.147
[gasps and wheezes]

1:21:42.147 --> 1:21:43.524
MARY: Shh.

1:21:43.524 --> 1:21:46.527
‐ [wheezes]

1:21:46.527 --> 1:21:50.197
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:21:50.197 --> 1:21:52.699
[choking coughs]

1:21:52.699 --> 1:21:55.869
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:21:55.869 --> 1:21:58.580
I'm so sorry.

1:21:58.580 --> 1:22:00.999
‐ [softly] It's okay.

1:22:00.999 --> 1:22:02.960
Shh.

1:22:02.960 --> 1:22:04.795
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:22:04.795 --> 1:22:06.797
Shh.
‐ [gasps]

1:22:06.797 --> 1:22:10.968
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:22:10.968 --> 1:22:13.971
<i>[eerie music]</i>

1:22:13.971 --> 1:22:20.978
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:22:22.688 --> 1:22:26.150
‐ $7.50.

1:22:26.150 --> 1:22:30.154
‐ Yes.
‐ Thanks.

1:22:30.154 --> 1:22:31.864
‐ Ooh.
I'm sorry.

1:22:31.864 --> 1:22:34.700
I think I left my wallet
in my other coat.

1:22:34.700 --> 1:22:36.243
‐ I got you.

1:22:36.243 --> 1:22:38.537
[rock music playing]

1:22:38.537 --> 1:22:41.039
Oh, fuck.

1:22:41.039 --> 1:22:43.125
‐ Would you allow us
to take these with us,

1:22:43.125 --> 1:22:46.545
and then we'll come by later
and pay you?

1:22:46.545 --> 1:22:48.630
‐ Yeah, no can do.

1:22:48.630 --> 1:22:49.631
‐ Really?

1:22:49.631 --> 1:22:52.259
‐ Wow, man.
Wha‐‐[scoffs]

1:22:52.259 --> 1:22:55.179
‐ That's gonna be $7.50.

1:22:55.179 --> 1:22:57.931
‐ Do you know Ravenmoor?

1:22:57.931 --> 1:22:59.141
‐ Yeah.

1:22:59.141 --> 1:23:01.393
BENNETT:
Is it a nice place?

1:23:01.393 --> 1:23:02.895
‐ No.

1:23:02.895 --> 1:23:04.813
‐ Well, we're headed there.

1:23:04.813 --> 1:23:08.692
Unless you want to join us
in the trunk of our car,

1:23:08.692 --> 1:23:10.611
you'll surrender
these beverages to us

1:23:10.611 --> 1:23:12.070
and allow us to pay you later,

1:23:12.070 --> 1:23:16.241
and you will do it very quickly
so they do not get cold.

1:23:17.659 --> 1:23:20.370
‐ Okay, these are on the house.
‐ Thank you very much.

1:23:20.370 --> 1:23:21.830
<i>[engine turns over]</i>

1:23:21.830 --> 1:23:24.833
[tires squeal]

1:23:26.251 --> 1:23:27.503
Hey, hey!
‐ Oh, fuck!

1:23:27.503 --> 1:23:28.670
[tires squeal]

1:23:28.670 --> 1:23:29.963
[horn blares]

1:23:29.963 --> 1:23:33.175
[engine revving]

1:23:33.175 --> 1:23:34.843
Fucking kids
with their headphones.

1:23:34.843 --> 1:23:37.054
Generation of zombies, man.
Sorry, B.

1:23:37.054 --> 1:23:38.639
‐ Whatever, man.

1:23:41.058 --> 1:23:44.061
<i>[ominous music]</i>

1:23:44.061 --> 1:23:51.109
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:24:10.712 --> 1:24:12.214
STEVE: Place is
royally fucked up, man.

1:24:12.214 --> 1:24:14.716
Some bad shit happened here
when I was a kid.

1:24:14.716 --> 1:24:18.554
Everybody knows this whole
neighborhood is haunted.

1:24:18.554 --> 1:24:20.222
Hey, do you even know
where we're going?

1:24:20.222 --> 1:24:21.807
‐ 47 Tollington Place.

1:24:21.807 --> 1:24:23.058
It's probably
up the street here,

1:24:23.058 --> 1:24:24.184
a few blocks away.

1:24:24.184 --> 1:24:26.103
Just keep driving.

1:24:26.103 --> 1:24:28.313
[cell phone rings]
‐ Oh, fuck.

1:24:28.313 --> 1:24:30.190
Shit, who's that, man?

1:24:30.190 --> 1:24:31.900
‐ That is my happy place.

1:24:31.900 --> 1:24:34.069
We get this book,
get out of here,

1:24:34.069 --> 1:24:36.363
I'm buying a condo in Mexico
on the beach.

1:24:36.363 --> 1:24:38.240
Me and Jeannie,
we're gonna sip tequilas

1:24:38.240 --> 1:24:41.410
and watch the divorcees
doing downward‐facing dog

1:24:41.410 --> 1:24:42.744
on the yoga lawn.

1:24:42.744 --> 1:24:44.621
‐ [laughs]

1:24:44.621 --> 1:24:45.998
‐ And I'm gonna read.

1:24:45.998 --> 1:24:49.876
Gonna read <i>Jack Reacher</i>
and William Shakespeare

1:24:49.876 --> 1:24:52.212
and leave the fucking rats
in the sewer.

1:24:52.212 --> 1:24:53.297
<i>[dramatic sting]</i>
‐ Whoa!

1:24:53.297 --> 1:24:54.923
[tires squeal]

1:24:54.923 --> 1:24:56.008
‐ What the fuck, man?

1:24:56.008 --> 1:24:57.259
‐ You see that, man?

1:24:57.259 --> 1:24:59.136
There was a‐‐
there was a woman, man.

1:24:59.136 --> 1:25:02.014
‐ What woman?
‐ She was just right there.

1:25:02.014 --> 1:25:05.517
[car rumbling]

1:25:06.685 --> 1:25:08.478
Aw, shit.
[engine sputtering]

1:25:08.478 --> 1:25:10.105
Aw, no, no, no, no.

1:25:10.105 --> 1:25:12.316
‐ Okay, pop the hood.

1:25:15.611 --> 1:25:16.862
[car door closes]

1:25:25.078 --> 1:25:27.164
‐ Hey, uh, what's wrong, B?

1:25:27.164 --> 1:25:28.915
‐ Hold on.

1:25:33.211 --> 1:25:35.505
[person moaning]

1:25:37.799 --> 1:25:40.344
<i>[dramatic sting]</i>

1:25:40.344 --> 1:25:45.474
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:25:45.474 --> 1:25:47.601
<i>PERSON: Stevie...</i>

1:25:49.770 --> 1:25:52.564
[voices whispering]

1:25:52.564 --> 1:25:55.275
<i>[eerie music]</i>

1:25:55.275 --> 1:25:57.986
BENNETT:
Try it now.

1:25:57.986 --> 1:26:00.530
Dude, you hear me?

1:26:00.530 --> 1:26:04.201
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:26:04.201 --> 1:26:07.162
Hey, bro, where you going?

1:26:07.162 --> 1:26:09.373
Where the fuck you going, man?

1:26:09.373 --> 1:26:10.666
Steve!

1:26:15.629 --> 1:26:20.676
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:26:20.676 --> 1:26:23.679
Steve?
Are you praying, man?

1:26:23.679 --> 1:26:26.431
To God?

1:26:26.431 --> 1:26:29.059
'Cause I guarantee
He ain't listening.

1:26:29.059 --> 1:26:31.061
STEVE:
Nah. Not God, B.

1:26:31.061 --> 1:26:32.771
‐ Then who?

1:26:32.771 --> 1:26:34.314
STEVE:
My mom, man.

1:26:34.314 --> 1:26:36.108
BENNETT: Your mom?
STEVE: Yeah.

1:26:36.108 --> 1:26:40.570
Yeah, you remember my mom, B?

1:26:40.570 --> 1:26:42.739
BENNETT:
Of course I remember your mom.

1:26:42.739 --> 1:26:44.533
‐ [laughs]
BENNETT: Amazing lady.

1:26:44.533 --> 1:26:47.661
‐ Yeah, she is.

1:26:47.661 --> 1:26:51.456
BENNETT:
Tell her I say hey.

1:26:51.456 --> 1:26:54.626
‐ She says, uh‐‐she says
she always liked you, B.

1:26:54.626 --> 1:26:58.505
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:26:58.505 --> 1:27:00.507
BENNETT: What the fuck?

1:27:00.507 --> 1:27:02.342
What are you doing, Steve?

1:27:02.342 --> 1:27:05.303
‐ She wants me
to come with her, man.

1:27:05.303 --> 1:27:07.389
‐ Put the gun down, man.

1:27:07.389 --> 1:27:09.599
‐ Oh, it's nice where she is.

1:27:09.599 --> 1:27:13.061
You know, it's a‐‐
it's a happy place, man.

1:27:13.061 --> 1:27:15.772
‐ Brother, listen to me.

1:27:15.772 --> 1:27:18.358
You were right, man.

1:27:18.358 --> 1:27:20.527
There's nothing here for us.

1:27:22.696 --> 1:27:24.906
[gunshot, inhuman scream]

1:27:28.034 --> 1:27:31.037
<i>[eerie music building]</i>

1:27:31.037 --> 1:27:38.003
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:27:38.003 --> 1:27:41.006
[breathing heavily]

1:27:47.721 --> 1:27:50.015
[engine turns over, revs]

1:27:50.015 --> 1:27:54.186
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:27:54.186 --> 1:27:56.188
[engine revs]

1:27:58.815 --> 1:28:00.233
[tires squeal]

1:28:00.233 --> 1:28:03.195
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

1:28:03.195 --> 1:28:10.202
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:28:14.706 --> 1:28:17.667
[rats squeaking]

1:28:17.667 --> 1:28:24.508
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:28:40.524 --> 1:28:43.527
<i>[eerie music]</i>

1:28:43.527 --> 1:28:50.534
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:29:05.882 --> 1:29:08.718
[door creaks]

1:29:49.509 --> 1:29:50.760
[person laughing]

1:29:50.760 --> 1:29:53.847
<i>[dramatic sting]</i>

1:29:53.847 --> 1:29:56.850
<i>[suspenseful music building]</i>

1:29:56.850 --> 1:30:03.899
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:30:16.494 --> 1:30:19.289
[door creaks]

1:30:19.289 --> 1:30:25.420
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:30:27.172 --> 1:30:29.633
Where is it?

1:30:29.633 --> 1:30:31.968
‐ What?

1:30:31.968 --> 1:30:33.345
‐ The book.

1:30:35.263 --> 1:30:37.015
Don't fuck with me, lady.

1:30:37.015 --> 1:30:39.309
Just give me what I want,
and I'll go.

1:30:39.309 --> 1:30:41.686
‐ Oh, I don't think you know
what you want...

1:30:47.525 --> 1:30:48.985
Or where you're going.

1:30:48.985 --> 1:30:50.904
‐ Believe it or not,
I don't want to have to kill

1:30:50.904 --> 1:30:52.405
anybody else today.

1:30:52.405 --> 1:30:56.910
So I'm asking you one
last time, where's the book?

1:30:56.910 --> 1:30:57.911
‐ What book?

1:30:57.911 --> 1:31:00.205
<i>‐ The Book of Blood.</i>

1:31:00.205 --> 1:31:03.124
‐ Oh, that book.

1:31:03.124 --> 1:31:04.668
Well, you're looking at it.

1:31:04.668 --> 1:31:06.795
[rocking chair creaking]

1:31:06.795 --> 1:31:08.713
And it's looking at you.

1:31:10.465 --> 1:31:12.550
‐ What happened to him?

1:31:12.550 --> 1:31:15.804
‐ You see,
all the dead have stories.

1:31:15.804 --> 1:31:17.639
In fact, that's all they have.

1:31:17.639 --> 1:31:21.184
And they chose Simon...

1:31:21.184 --> 1:31:23.019
to be their page.

1:31:23.019 --> 1:31:27.649
He lives on so that the dead
can have a voice.

1:31:27.649 --> 1:31:29.275
‐ Who are you?

1:31:29.275 --> 1:31:31.194
What are you doing here?

1:31:31.194 --> 1:31:33.405
‐ I'm his sole reader.

1:31:33.405 --> 1:31:34.447
The dead can be heard

1:31:34.447 --> 1:31:36.741
all around
these abandoned streets.

1:31:36.741 --> 1:31:38.785
But all roads lead to Simon,

1:31:38.785 --> 1:31:41.454
where the highways
first opened.

1:31:41.454 --> 1:31:44.624
Because of Simon,
I'm exactly where I want to be.

1:31:44.624 --> 1:31:46.960
I'm in my happy place.

1:31:49.504 --> 1:31:52.257
‐ I just want the book, lady.

1:31:52.257 --> 1:31:54.968
So, if he's the fucking book,
then I'm taking him with me.

1:31:54.968 --> 1:31:56.219
‐ You're not the first,

1:31:56.219 --> 1:31:57.971
and you certainly will not be
the last,

1:31:57.971 --> 1:31:59.848
to seek <i>The Book of Blood.</i>

1:31:59.848 --> 1:32:03.101
See, all their stories are
on him, too...

1:32:03.101 --> 1:32:05.729
as yours will be.

1:32:05.729 --> 1:32:08.857
You've been writing your story
your whole life.

1:32:08.857 --> 1:32:11.985
And now it's time
to come to its end.

1:32:11.985 --> 1:32:13.486
‐ My story doesn't end here.

1:32:13.486 --> 1:32:15.989
‐ All stories end here.

1:32:15.989 --> 1:32:22.996
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:32:24.622 --> 1:32:27.625
[scrabbling]

1:32:27.625 --> 1:32:30.795
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:32:30.795 --> 1:32:33.798
[rats squeaking]

1:32:33.798 --> 1:32:38.094
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:32:38.094 --> 1:32:40.930
‐ [screams]
Fuck! Get off!

1:32:40.930 --> 1:32:43.933
[rats screeching]

1:32:43.933 --> 1:32:49.481
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:32:49.481 --> 1:32:51.232
[rat screeches]

1:32:51.232 --> 1:32:57.781
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:32:57.781 --> 1:33:00.784
[moaning]

1:33:00.784 --> 1:33:07.791
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:33:32.649 --> 1:33:35.652
[indistinct chatter]

1:33:42.033 --> 1:33:44.160
SAM: All right, one, two,
three, and...

1:33:44.160 --> 1:33:46.621
[grunting]
‐ [coughs]

1:33:46.621 --> 1:33:50.834
SAM: How much cake
did you eat tonight?

1:33:50.834 --> 1:33:54.170
[grunting]

1:34:02.345 --> 1:34:04.055
Can I help you with something?

1:34:04.055 --> 1:34:07.058
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

1:34:07.058 --> 1:34:13.940
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:34:19.070 --> 1:34:21.281
‐ Got to protect the garden.

1:34:21.281 --> 1:34:24.284
<i>[tense music]</i>

1:34:24.284 --> 1:34:31.291
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:34:34.460 --> 1:34:37.088
[machines beeping]

1:34:37.088 --> 1:34:38.506
‐ [grunts]

1:34:38.506 --> 1:34:45.513
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:34:48.099 --> 1:34:49.809
SHERIFF:
Recognize him?

1:34:49.809 --> 1:34:51.936
NICOLE: I believe that's
the father of her ex‐boyfriend.

1:34:51.936 --> 1:34:54.355
SHERIFF: You probably heard
about what happened to the boy?

1:34:54.355 --> 1:34:56.858
‐ Jenna was quite broken up
about it.

1:34:56.858 --> 1:34:58.443
She hasn't been herself since.

1:34:58.443 --> 1:35:00.528
SHERIFF: You ever meet him?
Or the father?

1:35:00.528 --> 1:35:01.905
NICOLE: No.

1:35:01.905 --> 1:35:05.325
Well, he tried to see us.
He wanted to talk to Jenna.

1:35:05.325 --> 1:35:07.577
I wouldn't let him.
SHERIFF: Why is that?

1:35:07.577 --> 1:35:10.997
‐ What good would it have done,
dredging all that up?

1:35:10.997 --> 1:35:12.582
I mean, the boy was dead.

1:35:12.582 --> 1:35:14.709
No fault of Jenna's.

1:35:14.709 --> 1:35:16.753
She needed to move on
with her life.

1:35:16.753 --> 1:35:18.755
‐ He believed
your daughter was responsible

1:35:18.755 --> 1:35:20.256
for his son's death.

1:35:20.256 --> 1:35:21.549
He stalked her for some time

1:35:21.549 --> 1:35:23.343
and then either convinced her
to meet

1:35:23.343 --> 1:35:25.553
or snatched her off the street
and then drugged her.

1:35:25.553 --> 1:35:27.764
Vehicle software shows
that it was parked

1:35:27.764 --> 1:35:29.015
before it sped off the cliff.

1:35:29.015 --> 1:35:30.975
That and the lack
of any skid marks

1:35:30.975 --> 1:35:34.354
or signs of braking suggest
that this was no accident.

1:35:34.354 --> 1:35:38.149
Best guess‐‐he was aiming
for suicide and murder,

1:35:38.149 --> 1:35:40.777
but only succeeded
in the first part.

1:35:40.777 --> 1:35:42.654
DOCTOR:
Your daughter is very lucky.

1:35:42.654 --> 1:35:45.615
I have no doubt that
physically she will be fine.

1:35:45.615 --> 1:35:47.784
She has little memory
of what happened,

1:35:47.784 --> 1:35:49.744
but given the drugs
and the trauma,

1:35:49.744 --> 1:35:51.579
that's not unexpected,

1:35:51.579 --> 1:35:53.414
maybe even a blessing.

1:35:53.414 --> 1:36:00.380
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:36:06.177 --> 1:36:09.013
[chewing]
NICOLE: Want to talk about it?

1:36:11.432 --> 1:36:13.685
It's okay.
That's fine.

1:36:13.685 --> 1:36:15.353
You don't have to say a word.

1:36:15.353 --> 1:36:17.313
[chewing]

1:36:17.313 --> 1:36:19.607
Mom's gonna take care
of everything.

1:36:19.607 --> 1:36:23.236
[chewing and slurping
crescendo]

1:36:23.236 --> 1:36:26.739
[spinner whirs]

1:36:26.739 --> 1:36:27.824
All right.

1:36:27.824 --> 1:36:29.951
[game piece tapping]

1:36:29.951 --> 1:36:31.536
Lucky girl.

1:36:31.536 --> 1:36:33.663
Hmm.
A law degree.

1:36:33.663 --> 1:36:35.999
‐ Nice.
You're set for life.

1:36:35.999 --> 1:36:37.208
[loud crunch]

1:36:51.222 --> 1:36:54.225
<i>[somber music]</i>

1:36:54.225 --> 1:37:01.274
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:37:05.737 --> 1:37:07.196
<i>TONY:</i>
<i>I wish you were here.</i>

1:37:07.196 --> 1:37:09.282
<i>JENNA:</i>
<i>Wherever we are is here.</i>

1:37:09.282 --> 1:37:10.908
<i>TONY:</i>
<i>I know, but still...</i>

1:37:12.577 --> 1:37:14.912
Tell me again
about the first time.

1:37:14.912 --> 1:37:18.583
‐ You were right behind me
in that ridiculous class.

1:37:18.583 --> 1:37:20.501
‐ Deconstructing
the Neoliberal Gaze.

1:37:20.501 --> 1:37:22.503
<i>JENNA: And you looked</i>
<i>over my shoulder</i>

1:37:22.503 --> 1:37:24.130
<i>and saw me drawing everyone.</i>

1:37:24.130 --> 1:37:25.673
‐ Like a horde
of zombie lemmings

1:37:25.673 --> 1:37:27.675
marching off the edge
of a cliff.

1:37:27.675 --> 1:37:29.886
‐ And you leaned in

1:37:29.886 --> 1:37:32.680
and whispered into my ear...

1:37:32.680 --> 1:37:36.934
"Life is a problem
in search of a solution."

1:37:36.934 --> 1:37:39.020
I knew
we were meant for each other.

1:37:39.020 --> 1:37:40.271
<i>TONY:</i>
<i>We are.</i>

1:37:40.271 --> 1:37:42.273
I just wish‐‐
<i>JENNA: What?</i>

1:37:42.273 --> 1:37:45.151
‐ That we could be together.

1:37:45.151 --> 1:37:47.153
‐ We're joining
the great, infinite nothing.

1:37:47.153 --> 1:37:48.488
We will be together.

1:37:48.488 --> 1:37:50.907
‐ No, I mean...

1:37:50.907 --> 1:37:53.493
when we do it,
we could do it together.

1:37:53.493 --> 1:37:56.788
‐ No, don't you see?
It's not just about us.

1:37:56.788 --> 1:37:58.956
It's about the sign
we leave behind us,

1:37:58.956 --> 1:38:01.709
the footprints in the sand
showing others the way.

1:38:01.709 --> 1:38:03.503
<i>Our folks, all the students,</i>

1:38:03.503 --> 1:38:05.129
they'll just think
it was about us,

1:38:05.129 --> 1:38:06.506
that we were in love and‐‐

1:38:06.506 --> 1:38:08.174
‐ I am in love with you.

1:38:08.174 --> 1:38:10.593
‐ Me too,
but that's not the point.

1:38:10.593 --> 1:38:13.096
<i>It'll completely muddy</i>
<i>the message.</i>

1:38:13.096 --> 1:38:14.305
‐ The message?

1:38:14.305 --> 1:38:16.641
‐ That life is a lie,

1:38:16.641 --> 1:38:18.518
that we said no
to all the bullshit,

1:38:18.518 --> 1:38:22.605
that we chose the freedom
of annihilation.

1:38:22.605 --> 1:38:24.190
‐ Right.

1:38:26.859 --> 1:38:28.194
‐ If you want out, just say it.

1:38:28.194 --> 1:38:30.822
‐ No, I‐I just‐‐

1:38:30.822 --> 1:38:33.825
<i>[ominous music]</i>

1:38:33.825 --> 1:38:37.787
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:38:37.787 --> 1:38:39.872
‐ Okay, try this.

1:38:39.872 --> 1:38:42.208
Close your eyes.

1:38:42.208 --> 1:38:44.085
<i>Picture me.</i>

1:38:44.085 --> 1:38:47.171
I'm right there with you.
We'll do it at the same time.

1:38:48.756 --> 1:38:50.758
You're on the roof, right?

1:38:50.758 --> 1:38:53.094
Me too.

1:38:53.094 --> 1:38:54.470
<i>TONY:</i>
<i>I want to.</i>

1:38:54.470 --> 1:38:56.597
I really, really do.

1:38:58.433 --> 1:39:01.394
I just don't think I can.
I'm scared.

1:39:01.394 --> 1:39:04.230
<i>JENNA: If you don't do it now,</i>
<i>you're never gonna do it.</i>

1:39:06.149 --> 1:39:08.025
I thought you understood.

1:39:09.444 --> 1:39:11.028
‐ I'm getting off the ledge.

1:39:11.028 --> 1:39:13.906
‐ No, don't you dare,
you fucking coward!

1:39:13.906 --> 1:39:15.450
‐ Okay.

1:39:17.743 --> 1:39:19.162
I'm still here.

1:39:19.162 --> 1:39:22.457
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:39:22.457 --> 1:39:24.917
‐ Okay, good.

1:39:24.917 --> 1:39:27.670
Now we just do it, together.

1:39:27.670 --> 1:39:29.046
We do it right now, okay?

1:39:29.046 --> 1:39:32.258
We just fucking do it now!

1:39:32.258 --> 1:39:35.261
<i>[somber music]</i>

1:39:35.261 --> 1:39:37.638
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:39:37.638 --> 1:39:39.724
<i>Hello?</i>

1:39:39.724 --> 1:39:44.353
[sobbing]

1:39:44.353 --> 1:39:47.690
<i>Tony?</i>

1:39:47.690 --> 1:39:48.900
<i>Hello?</i>

1:39:48.900 --> 1:39:55.907
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:40:28.356 --> 1:40:31.359
<i>[tense music]</i>

1:40:31.359 --> 1:40:38.366
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:40:48.543 --> 1:40:51.546
<i>[quietly eerie music]</i>

1:40:51.546 --> 1:40:58.553
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:42:04.285 --> 1:42:07.288
<i>[music builds]</i>

1:42:07.288 --> 1:42:14.253
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:42:28.893 --> 1:42:31.896
[exhales deeply]

1:42:36.275 --> 1:42:39.278
<i>[eerie music]</i>

1:42:39.278 --> 1:42:45.201
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:42:45.201 --> 1:42:49.914
‐ So many stories, my love.

1:42:49.914 --> 1:42:51.874
So many stories.

1:42:51.874 --> 1:42:54.418
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:42:54.418 --> 1:42:56.420
Whose will be next?

1:42:56.420 --> 1:43:03.427
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:43:08.933 --> 1:43:11.936
